\par }\pard \ltrpar\qj \fi-461\li461\ri0\sa240\widctlpar\wrapdefault\aspalpha\aspnum\faauto\adjustright\rin0\lin461\itap0\pararsid8407077 {\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Could you tell me where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 It was - they used to call it 
- the Bottoms - it was Brook Street, a lot of little back to back houses and - it came to the bottom of Heathcote Street when you came out there.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How many years did you live in the house where you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I'd be a very little child, we moved quite a few times as the family grew bigger you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Can you remember how many times you moved and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 why}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  you moved, was it every time because the family was getting bigger?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 We wanted - yes, there were some very tiny ones and - by the time - mother
 had thirteen children so you can imagine she had to - get a bit bigger house. I can remember - living - on Gordon Road. I went to school from there. And I can also remember - I think even before Gordon Road it was - Silv}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 erwood}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  Place, Bellagate, which come
s off the lace market, you see, I lived there quite a long while, I should think I should be getting on for eight or nine when we moved from there. I went to St Mary's church school there. And - we moved again and this time we went to Gordon Road because 
there was another bedroom, my brothers were growing up you see. And then we moved to - from there to Union Terrace. And - then we moved across from Union Terrace, their backs were together but - backs in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 Heatherly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  Street this side, they had another bedroom so we had to move again. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 
And - mother was at fourteen - four Heatherly Street and I was ten when - just over ten I should think I'd be when I went to Bath Street school first and then I got a scholarship and went to Huntingdon Street school, which was a pa
ying school in those days you know, and actually I was married from mother's and I lived in her two rooms - over four years before I got a house, and then that was further up the street. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
It was far too big for me but I was so pleased to get a house. And then I moved to Sherwood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Which house would you have lived in the longest as a child do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
I can remember the longest - I was quite a big girl when I went to Bath Street school I can - I'm taking it more from my own age you see, don't know exactly the years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Which one were you in the longest?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well it lays between Gordon Road and Union Terrace and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 Headley}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  Street. Union Terrace and Headley Street were sort of one street, back to back like. It lays within those and I was just about 
ten when I first went there and I was married from there, see. That's the longest I can remember.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How many brothers and sisters did you have and their birth order and spacing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh - now you've set me a problem. I wish I'd got father's Bible here
. I did try to ask - my daughter came last week and - thought I had - did I mention to you this great big wonderful Bible from the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 Ragged}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  School. It was calf bound and gold lettering on, from when he was a boy attending this school. And - ready - put all our }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 births}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  in the Bible, as soon as the new baby was born the - the date - I can - I can }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 only}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  judge by - my own age from the others.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Where did you come in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 Well actually I'm the seventh girl. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
And I have - up and down - yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What is your Christian name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Annie. Mother didn't believe in fancy names, you got one name. We - I had - the eldest one, sister was Elizabeth. These were married, these first three before I can remember anything you see. Jemima, the next one, was appr
oximately two - sometimes three years between them. Julia. Alice. And she had a girl, Harriet, that died. So the next one happened to be a boy and she called him Albert. Then the next one she had was a girls she got Harriet because of - the - the poor Har
riet had died.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 This happened a lot didn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Very much so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you think people minded being called after somebody who had died?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no, they loved it. And we were all somehow or other - all we sisters, we sort of thought a special lot 
of Harriet. I don't know why - mind she was a lovely girl, but we did. I used to think she was wonderful. You see, she was so much older than I and she - be - I was the one that was in - little toddler, she wanted something, go on you go. And she - but sh
e
 was very kind to me when I was ill. She'd take me to bed and sing me to sleep and I've never forgotten it. And she - she - you know, she was more kind to the others was too grown up and she would tag me about and I - I said to her, did you want to go by 
yourself Harriet? No, she said, you're quiet so I don't mind. I loved her. I - I loved them all but that one I think in particular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You never felt that she felt she was replacing somebody else?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. Mother made her take me you see, I was the one 
that was - she'd two babies after that and - she couldn't put the babies on to Harriet as well, somebody else had to have the baby.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You were after Harriet then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, Grace. And then me. Annie. And then my brother John. And then I had another litt
le sister Ruth. These two both died in infancy but I can remember then quite well. And then Arthur. He was the last one that I can remember but - mother's told me since, she used to often tell me bits, that she'd miscarried twins or something all along th
is line which made that she'd had actually thirteen children you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did the boys come out of this, you were a very feminine family weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh I was sorry for my older brother. Because mother and dad and all the girls treated him as a g
irl. Yes. Used to make him wash up. He was terrified of dad, he wasn't cruel to him, but - you get that dish cloth and you wipe up while the girls'll wash. And he used to look like this. But he was very kind to me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 He'd give me rides on his shoulders and in this Silverwood place where we lived - you won't know about the burials, there were three distinct burial grounds, and our yard came to the end of one. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 There was a brick wall and railings. And I'd say, go on Albert, just be my horse, just up and down. He
'd ride me up on his shoulders and he'd let me hang on to the railings and look right over Nottingham. I thought he was wonderful. And - and then once he got me up there and he says, oh look, he says, there's a fire. He could see it over Cartergate way - 
q
uite a long way. I said, oh yes. He says, if you promise not to tell your dad I'll take you. It was evening time. And he did - took me on his shoulders, he galloped along, he let me - pretend to - whip him and - I thought he was wonderful. And - it was De
a
con Street factory on Congleton Road, it was absolutely gutted. And of course Albert was so interested in it all, he'd no idea of the time and of course I was too young to know. And I'll always remember dad was a little man. I said, Albert how's it going 
o
n? And dad patted him on the shoulder - it's one o'clock in the morning. What do you mean he said, by keeping this child out like this? There was crowds of people there though, of course Albert was one of the crowd. I've never forgotten that. And he - I'l
l
 give you a whipping I get you home my lad. He says this poor child's falling asleep. I said, I'm not dad. I said, I like to see it. You be quiet. Because we were the young ones, weren't supposed to be heard in that little crowd. And of course the - he wa
s - he was only like dad, dad liked to go an see a fire. He did. But - it was so wonderful to me, the experience, I said, never been up as a late as that in my life have I? He said, no dear you haven't and you'll not be again, he says, he said to me.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You say there were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 roughly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  two or three years between you all?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
There was - yes. We were - we were quite contented family. We had very little. 'Cos father never earned any money really. Not a - however they lived I don't know. It was mother's churning
 and - what bit he could - we didn't go without food and - she was such a wonderful needlewoman. She could make any old thing look nice you know. Oh she was wonderful. I wished I could have done what she did but - of course I wasn't clever enough.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Can you remember how old your father was when you were born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
When I was born? No, I don't but I do - I've heard me eldest sister saying, from time to time, mother was only seventeen when she got married, and he was eighteen. And dad was only a year olde
r than her. But I don't know - the - the - I used to know the - the month they were born in but I've forgotten it. And it's - it's in the old Bible but of course I haven't got it. Joyce has taken it to Boots to be repaired for me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you know why they married so young, it was very young to marry for those days wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 Yes, very, very - yes, it was very young. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
They lived near each other, dad lived at the back of Batlock on Coltham Street, one of the streets that ran off there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you know where your father came from, where he was born?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - Nottingham people born and bred all of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When he was married what was his occupation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - his - in those days the - the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 hand frames}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  were doing the hosiery, the - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 power frames}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  ha
dn't been invested in those days and in these little tine back to back houses there were two bedrooms one above the other, then what we called the shop with windows all the way along - yes - and you - they're all pulled down now but they're out - there's 
quite a lot left out in the countryside, Keyworth and all round there where they did a lot of this work, and - they used to hire the frames from - Nine or }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 Morley\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  and several more hosiery places, and all the boys would walk up - the father sort of was the 
foreman and he taught them all to do this, but it was shockingly paid. They made this hosiery by hand on these - it was a sort of knitting machine really, made ever such a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999  funny}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  noise and - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 grandad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 lived to be quite old and - but his other brothers - struck against it. They were - grand}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
ad was a very - a martinet, you know what I mean and - dad was the only one who'd put up with it, so he used to say, you'll have to take over the shop when I go. But - unfortunately, when he died grandma said she'd had quite
 enough of the shop and she sent the frames back so me dad had nothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What would he be then then?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well I - I - I could read and write and I'd gone to school so I should be approximately - perhaps ten or twelve - more like twelve I think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So what happened then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
So - anyway we were talking it over and I said, it was unkind of gran to do that wasn't it dad? You haven't nothing have you? He said, no. I said, well - you used to take the work into Hine Ormeleys for grandfather, should I d
raft you a letter out and you copy it and ask them -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So you did the writing for him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes. In this time, 'cos he couldn't write. That's when I began to teach him to write you see. So he said - won't be any good. Oh, I said, don't be downhearted, 
it may be. I said, if they only gave you just one frame for yourself you'd be something. So he took a lot of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 persuading}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
, he wasn't a man who could - you know, force himself. So mother says, well it's no - no harm in giving a - try, she could write.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You were what age then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 About twelve I should think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You were taking the initiative in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well I wouldn't say initiative, I was thinking for dad because he was so unhappy and I tried to think of away because I thought it was unkind 
of gran to have - taken his livelihood away from him. We used to talk it over with me eldest sister, the one next to me, Grace. She used to say, go on, I dare you to do it. I said, well I can't - I'm not going to do anything wrong, Grace, just ask this ma
n
 if he could give dad a frame just to bring a - for himself. So she says, does he know his name? I said, yes, he does. Can't remember it now but anyway - and I wrote this letter for him and I - guided his hand to sign his name at the bottom. I said, now y
o
u take it dad, and don't give it to anybody, this was the man who gave the work out sort of. And he came back and he said - I was - oh - you know, so excited. Well what did they say to you? And mother says, you be quiet. I said - well I want to know. He's
 
going to give it his - he tried to think how to say it - he thought - I think it was, careful consideration, what does it mean, he says. 'Cos he'd had no education whatsoever, except these few hours at the Ragged School on a Sunday afternoon, so of course
 
- wasn't many days and this letter came and it was printed and I taught him how to read print first. And it says, will you please call at there and we will arrange for a frame. Have you room at hour home for it? - And all this. And it was fixed up in no t
i
me. And we got a bedroom, we never used it, no furniture in it, it was a cellar kitchen house, have you ever seen one of them? Well - your living room - opened onto the back yard. And then there was a sort of pantry place underneath the front room, went u
p
 the first stairs to the front room and then you was an a garden, you see, but there was a door to go up it. But - it was - over - it was sort of along with the first bedroom and the kitchen was sort of underneath, that's why they called them cellar kitch
ens.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Could you get down to the kitchen from the outside as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes. Yes. With a little backyard. That was for the - the back entrance. And we had a - fair size living room and scullery. And then this big pantry we used to call it, with stone s
labs all round. And this - all that kind of thing. But - this front room was empty so - we scrubbed it out, we worked so hard and we got it really nice. Bare boards with nothing on. And of course we were all fascinated when it came but we didn't like it w
hen we heard the noise it made.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 Was it very, very noisy?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well it - he - it wasn't - it went sssssh. That was when he was running the thread along and then it was worked by a sort of - with his feet underneath to move the thing. It went t-pop-pop-
pop-pop, and we used to be - playing around but it did - it wasn't - mind you didn't have enough work to - keep it long, but - he kept that up until - they - these - all these old people who worked for them all these years, they used to give them little p
e
nsion. My grandad had five shilling - five shillings I think it was, yes, and grandmother when grandad died, they gave it to her. And - well - when - they had - dad hadn't been the having the frame at home ever so long when he came home very disheartened,
 
he said, they can't find me any more work. It was such expensive stuff to do by hand. It was like hand knitting you see. And they only did bit broads and ladies and that kind of thing. I mean now they'd got these things that went by steam and they could d
o
 hundreds of dozens. And they'd got this big factory on Newark Street, still there today, and - they said that they'd have to fetch the machines back, they were - this machine that dad had, it - they couldn't give him any more work. So that - so I said, w
ell did you not ask if they could find you a little job in the factory?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Me. Because I - I knew how worried mum'd be you see. So he said, well if it comes to that I could. He said, well I've got to go on Friday to fetch what bit was due
 to him. He said, and I'll - I said, don't go and ask for nothing - other than you ask that man who let you have the machine dad. He came back beaming. I said, well what happened? He said, yes. Oh, we had quite a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 jubilation}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 . They said all they could find him was a sweeping up job at the factory. But it was more money than he'd ever earned in his life.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Sweeping up compared with the skilled work he was doing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Than he was doing on that hand frame, that's absolute true. And again they used to have to
 do winding the yarn and it was just like a - an old fashioned spindle thing, but it had to be oiled and they had something to hold in their hands and it was only neatsfoot oil they could put on this sort of material, I don't know what it was, }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 merino}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  and all - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 botany}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
, all those kinds, and they said, you could do some winding in your spare time. And - any little odd job that came along. And he said - hours were from six in the morning 'til six at night and it was thirty shillings a week. I thought he would n
ever get over it. He said, fancy it, he said, thirty bob a week. He'd been getting about ten shillings on this for years. And he - but it's quite true. Yes, absolutely. And it really gave him new life. Of course, when it - when - after he was - what was i
t
 - I - they used to have to be seventy-four they got an old age pension then - in those days, I've forgotten his age when he got that. It was seventy wasn't it. And he - he - I've heard him telling me mum you see. When I'm - shan't be long before I'm seve
nty I'm - he said, I'll get me old age pension and - Morley's will give me a pension, they always do, and - he said, we shall be all right. He was so - elated you know. Then of course we got the letter to say how }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 Morley\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  were so very sorry - they'd brought
 in this - where men paid so much towards a pension if they'd worked at a factory and dad just fell flat before. And of course he'd never paid any-thing towards it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 
They said, we're very, very sorry but we've had to discontinue it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And he was the first man
 that - didn't get it. Of course we - Grace and Harriet and I and - we knew mum had been crying, she wouldn't like us to see her but Harriet says, well couldn't we do something for them. She went out to work, Julia went out to work, Grace went out to work
.
 We didn't earn much, we were all in the lace market. So our Harriet says, there's ten of us. If we each gave them a shilling surely we could that. It'd give him his independence. So we did. Decided - we went to the married ones, never told them anything 
'
til we were sure. And it - it was worth everything. There was one or two who lived out of Nottingham and they used to send it to them. It was about ten shillings. But we got these ten - the shilling a week. We all gave it, and then if we got a raise we'd 
give him an extra threepence, he thought it was wonderful.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So when did he actually retire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I was trying to remember.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did he work until he was seventy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 He must have done because the - the question of the pension wouldn't have arisen. No. Can't just remember exactly.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When he was working for himself and only getting ten bob a week how many hours a week did he work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Not very many you see. They gave him so much yarn and they knew exactly what it would do and they - they paid - pe
rhaps he'd have to say - you must make four vests out of this. Or - you must make two }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 vests}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 and two pairs those long pants men wore those days. Or even only one pair. And it all depended on the yarn that they could give him for the - the more he turned out
 he got a few shillings more, you see. But it got so bad because, you see, they got it to the - where they could get it - could make half a dozen while dad was doing one. Yes. And I believe - I'll tell you this, perhaps you'd like to go and see - I'm quit
e sure there's a - a hand frame in - in the castle. And I believe - I believe once he took us. I said, did you fit in there dad? Sit on it and do this, you know. Kids.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your father have a job before this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well he - mostly worked as a lad you see in his father's shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 From what age was he doing that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh they never went to school. Nine or ten I believe I've heard him say, but I couldn't be sure of that exactly, but they never went to school. So as soon as they could use their hands th
ey'd got to do - running errands and this winding. And anything they could, do, and I did - mother did - was telling me once that after they'd got married she felt he wasn't - grandma was a bit of a martinet and - and - she felt - mother felt that she did
n
't - wasn't quite fair to dad. She says, I should look round for some kind of a job and not be dependant on the old people. You see. And he did go for a while as a - steel rod - he trained for a steel rod maker, somewhere on Ashforth Street, off Hartford 
S
treet, I remember that quite well. And she - he was there for quite a while. But then there was a slump in the trade as there often is and dad was one of the last to go and the one that be most inexperienced so of course he went. He had to go. There was n
o more for him. And - then he went - he had a brother }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid13853716\charrsid14039999 who\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 gone to Yorkshire in a mine and he wrote and said, well I think you can get a job down here if you can come. And we all scratched up the train fare for him to go. But he - he couldn't - he - he wen
t and he went down below but - he was - not well, he didn't - and that, so - he came - he wasn't long away, he came back again. And - that was sort of the end of it until he got this frame for himself at home, you see, after grandad died. We were - seemed
 to be very much better.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was he actually out of work for long in these periods when he changed jobs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well I couldn't say. To me, as a child you don't - you - how long, it seemed a long while to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Because you were all worried?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, we
 were. Because, you know - we thought it was awful because he used to go so regularly to grandad's to be there - he'd have to be there by eight o'clock in the morning. And we lived - before they'd any children, they lived up Beverley Street, St }{
