\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She started this at what age?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Quite - oh - 'cos she'd never been to sc
hool, she was like dad. And as - I've heard her say that from a tiny little girl - her mother did it. Her sister did it. Before her. And - well it - in those days - round there if they didn't do lace work from the factories, the drawing and scalloping, th
ey did chebonning. Or hairnet spreading. But most - more women than men did because the men couldn't get the work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Could you explain what chebonning means?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Well, you yourself I suppose have bought your husband socks with - embroidery on like
 that on here and up there on the point. Well you'd never dream it's all done by hand but it is. And they can do it on the machine up to where the top is. I've put spots on by the hour by hand because they can't do them on the machines. No. And - but when
 
mother was little - and - the ladies all had - all - all beautiful little forget-me-nots, little sprays of lilies. The whole filed on top of stockings. Fine cashmere stockings - right up to the knee. About five or six rows. Oh I was fascinated by them. An
d there wasn't a - one - you couldn't go out, you'd got to keep it to the whales so as it was perfect. And talk about embroidery looks.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did they make up their designs?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, they were given a design. A pattern of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999 hose}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  they called it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How was the design given to them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
One hose - or stocking that somebody - more experienced inside the factory had done it and it was sent out and they'd give you a dozen - either stockings or socks, whichever it was, and you do it and you had the silk to work with and you would do this -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 It was done in silk was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Some was done in - most of it was done in silk, yes, and you had to do five or six threads, it was so very fine, thread it up and make it lay nice and flat. And - they had middle women wh
o fetch - well they used to send them hampers full of it, and then the people like mother have to go to her and pick up what she could - she'd spread it out amongst as many as she could, this lady. A dozen or two dozen. You see. And you'd got to get it do
ne by a certain time. And you do all sorts of patterns. We had more }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 men\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 socks than - the fancy fronts went out after that. I'm ever so sorry I destroyed them now but mother had a big bundle, she always believed in making a copy in case the - they wanted t
he pattern back before she'd sort of got it into her brain as she used to say. And I remember a long while after she says, 'ere, she says, you're the only one as can do it, you'd better take these. Scruffy bits of hose, the patterns was there all on them.
 Yes. I don't want them. I said. She said, go on you have them. And then once when I was spring leaning I said, I won't keep them any longer. It's dead, it's died out. Mind you I've done it - I've done - I've done a dozen }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 men\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  socks with these on - two on each sock, that's twenty-four in a dozen - for one and six a dozen. Imagine.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How long did it take you to do it for your one and six?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well you - you - after a while you get very quick. You have got to go in every time. it - ordinary cashmere, it 
was not - never silk of course. But you'd have to go in every one, you mustn't miss one, or your line wouldn't be straight, do you see. Oh it took a long while. Mind you, when - I was fascinated, I was always watching her, let me look - do - let me see if
 I - any my eldest sister she was a - she says, you're not going to do it. She says, you're pale faced enough as it is, you want to run and play the same as the other children. I says, I should just love to do -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You wanted to?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Because - I us
ed to think it was wonderful. I watched her. She always sat and - in the evenings when - especially in the winter you couldn't see them, they had gas lights you know and dad - there was a - looked like a cake tin to me - and he lit a globe like a - a - fi
sh - goldfish bowl and that had to g}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
t in it and standing at the back of this was full of something - I once asked dad what it - It looked like green water to me. And was this little - lamp.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You mean a magnifying glass?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, he called it - he said it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 aciplotus (?)}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 and water, I've always remembered it but it was I don't know. But - the lamp threw the light through the water. She'd get the hose on her hand and would keep it like that and she could like go - like this all the way, like lightenin
g. Yes. And we always used to say, we've got to be quiet, the lamps coming out. Because she - you see, if she was counting - you often had to count the stitches. You see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 This was an oil lamp she used?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, you can by them today - that hang o
n the wall with a - a round - silver plating at the back of it you see. That was in addition to the - we had gas - mantles you know didn't we, no electricity then. And - we were - we all liked to - and sometimes she'd sing to us. If she - it was me that s
he was familiar with. And stitch it. 'Course there was no television or anything like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So she went on doing this all her life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did she ever retire?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Not really. No. But - that died out too - you see. They did it by machiner
y what they could. And what they couldn't do - they used to train little girls in the factories to do. They didn't want to send it out. If they could possibly help it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When this worked stopped did your mother mind, did she miss the money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh she
 did miss the money but of course, there was quite a few of them then, there was - there was Julia, Alice, Harriet, Grace, myself - four - five - John, we were all paying our board. She would never take all our money, you must pay for your board as you ca
lled it, you see, and - the rents were so }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 shockingly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 low in those days, it was really - those houses although they were very - poor, they were - I think it was - nine shillings a week and there was four bedrooms, of course there was no bathroom - or anythin
g like that. Still we had a huge bath and - the boys had the bath one night and we had to go and sit upstairs while they bathed. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What sort of hours did your mother work on this chebonning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - she cooked the dinner - we did all the washi
ng up, it was - see, we all had - from the biggest to the littlest you'd all got your job to do. And she cooked the meal for the ten of us, quite sufficient to last her the morning. You had to fit it in before we went to school, we had to go to the butche
r
s and the greengrocers and - we got into the way of going and we - didn't mind it. Those that were at school and she'd cook it and it was all ready when we got home from school and she'd stack everything up in the sink and then when we'd had our tea in th
e
 evening we'd all the washing up to do and that kind of thing, and then she had to rest and - I don't - I never thought that she was ever so strong because she always told me - if I don't have that little rest on the afternoon I'm no good. And I - my litt
le mind couldn't take it. And yet she always seemed robust.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Didn't you tell me she did Queen Mary's ....?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Princess Mary's wedding - pure silk stockings for her wedding.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She wore them on the wedding day did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Well I couldn't say for sure that but I know }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 Morley\rquote s}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 sent her a dozen pairs - whether it was for a wedding present - oh we were so proud of her. And this lady - this dear old lady who used to give the work out and she came to mother's with this parcel, she said, I wan
t you to be sure to put a white - a clean white apron on when you do these. So mother said, I don't work anything if it's light without my clean white apron. She's got an apron for every job, mother had, oh yes. And she said - these are for Princess Mary.
 
You know, the one that's going to be married. And she had to put - H.R.H. - Her Royal Highness Princess Mary in cross stitching. And they were fine silk. When she showed her the pattern - I said, can I look mum? Oh, she said, you are nosey. So when Mrs Ha
llam had gone we let - she says, well now you can look. And it was cross stitching - not plain - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 stitches}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 for figures or letters. Oh but you couldn't tell a hand had touched them when she'd done them. And I really think she got a thrill out of it. She - eve
ry - it was - each stocking as she was doing it was rolled up in this white cloth so that nothing but just the part that she was doing - and she paid - forget how much she paid - I think double what she got for an ordinary job. Oh but no one would have th
o
ught it was worth the deed. It was - we were all just as excited as she was. Don't - keep your dirty fingers off - don't you dare touch them - if we went anywhere near it. Can't remember the date of that, and it was funny that - years after I went to Quee
nsmead from the British Legion and Princess Mary's home at Hull Dawes which is not far from there, we used to go a little walk down there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Which house are you going to tell us about?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 It'd be number seven Union Terrace where I can remember most.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How many rooms were there in the house at Union Terrace, was this the one with the basement kitchen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes. The - the - cellar kitchen, that was the - cellar kitchen. There's the living room. Scullery and then this - it was quite a bit room but cam
e under the garden at the front. That was - I think that's why they called it a cellar. The coal place was one half of it, where you stored the coal, and in the other - there was - stone slabs round to put your food. You see. And then there was the - fron
t
 room on the first flight of stairs up and the back bedroom went off together like that and there were two more bedrooms above there, quite big bedrooms. And then above that was a big attic that went across the whole of the house. There were - there were 
- plenty of room in for a family. You see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So the big room at the top was a bedroom?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 That was the room people would have used for the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 frames}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 They would have had for the shops. For the hand frames. They called them the shops.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What else did the word shop mean then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh well, you all - the little shop at the corner we always called it the shop. But these were - I should think it was an abbreviation of - workshop, you see. From what I could gather. But dad always calle
d it the shop. And when I've gone to take a message to me grandma's I can remember quite well going down - Cotham Street and I used to look up at the houses and used to say that's the living room, that's the other - oh and all those widows all up at the t
o
p and I asked me dad once, what's all those - he said, oh that's the shop love, where all the frames are. Else I didn't know. Yes, oh and he once took us to Kever, there was a lot of these little villages - I believe some of it's still done. Yes. And dad 
showed me, he says, they don't have to go up three flights to their shop.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So you used your front room for the machines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. While dad needed it and of course when they took it from - well we never really used it because there was no furniture in
 it. But we played in it, but we - rainy days you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 But it wouldn't count as a reception room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no. Not by any means.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How many living rooms were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only the one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What did you call it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 The kitchen. That was the ki
tchen. Yes, one living room, one scullery. One that had the sink in, and the copper. You know, one that you used to light the coal underneath with and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only your family was in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes. Wasn't room for any more. Of course the - one - e
ach time the - one sister got married there was always a bit more room for the rest of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Your mother wouldn't have had anyone to help in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no. Oh we - children - as soon as you could do little jobs, you'd each one got a job to do. 
The big girls - used to come home from work on a Friday, we had to blacklead the grate, there was a little old chimney fireplaces. Steel fender, oh and I loathed them. And if a spot of water dropped on it, it rusted, it would take you hours to do this. Bu
t it had got to be just so. Red tiled floors that were scrubbed. They had to be scrubbed Saturday and Sunday. We had white tablecloths on but we'd never any polished top. We had to scrub the top - everything had to be scrubbed. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 We used to have to scrub the stairs down, plain wood, that had to be white.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have a job each?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes. Well - we shared them if there was one got rather more than another, of if one got done first - and you sort of got a plan you wanted to get done quick and go out - they'd say - oh I'll help you to do that, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was it that the oldest had a certain job and they changed or did she stick to her job for life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well mostly. But they did all - work together. Mother did the washing but - you - we wore lost of blo
uses in those days. And - needleworkers we used to call it - underwear and - oh, the ironing. Hours and hours of it. If you wanted to go anywhere in particular and wanted to iron a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 blouse}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 , you'd got to do it yourself you see, and we always made the bed. Mo
ther only made her own bed. But when we were cleaning our bedrooms we cleaned mothers in with it because she - how could she. We didn't mind it, we didn't think we were hard done to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Your mother did the washing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And cooking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Imag
ine washing for ten. Look at the - oh - in an old dolly tub - well it was a dolly - it was a dolly tub and a ponch and she'd count them - you'd got - if you said, I'll dolly you for you mum. Yes, but just remember how many times I want it turning and you 
had got to remember. Old fashioned wringers, we used to fold them and turn the wheel. But I learned - we did - in fact we enjoyed life.
\par 
