don market when you could barely walk and there was always a stall that sold secondhand ones, and for a few coppers - I never had a pair of new shoes. None of us did. Mother had to pay just what she could, until we began to grow up
 and one or two of the elder ones went out to work. And there was a little shop when we lived on Union Road that - on St Ansell Road - and mother - I was sent with a message to her and she looked at me feet, this lady did. She says, they're poor shoes, th
e
y don't even fit you. And of course I was so proud you know. I said, my mother bought them me. So she said, who is your mother? So I said - I told her. She said, have you lived here long? I said - oh quite a while now. She said, ask mummy to come and have
 
a word with me will you? And I've never forgotten this, this has stuck in my mind. Form a little shop. So mother went, she said, what do you want to see me for? The shoe shop. And elderly lady and just her. She says, you're crippling that child, and in so
m
ebody else's shoes if you don't mind me saying so. So mother says, it's not intentional I can assures. She says, but - needs must. She says, we can't afford to buy them new ones, there's so many of them. So she said, well I'd like to make a bargain with y
o
u. She says, if you pay me so much a week, and I won't be hard on you, you can have - I'll refit them all out. And we all had new shoes. And until my mother - just before my mother died she paid the last money off that shoe bill. And I had to fit on for m
ine - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid5112414\charrsid14039999 I\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 got four little ones coming up and I could go there any time until she had to - they've pulled the shop down now and it's gone.
