\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were you expected to go to bed at a certain time in your schooldays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What sort of time would it have been?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well, it just depended - she didn't stick to any hard an
d fast rules. But if the other grown up ones were going to go out, then get these children to bed before you go sort of business. And - oh we wouldn't think it was any hardship. We used to lay and talk to each other if we didn't go to sleep.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your mother or anyone else put you to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No, not mother, she never did, it was - the other children or sometimes dad did. When I was young dad always carried me to bed and I loved that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 At what age did you put yourselves to bed, can you remember?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh we never stayed up late, not ever so late - when we were old enough to go to work and go out for a little while you had to be in at ten on Saturdays on without fail and nine on Sundays. And of course we were - we had to just have whatever there was
, a cup of cocoa or something and go straight to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You shared the bedroom with the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh - well this - there was a great big room, it was along with the original shop, yes, there was two double beds and a single bed, we all used to sleep - all the girls did. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 All the girls slept at the top?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. That's it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Who did you sleep with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Grace, my sister - the next sister to me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 There was a bedroom down belong was there for the boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Mother kept - there was o
ne a bit smaller and - me brother Albert slept in that one. And then when John came along - for a long while he slept with me while he was a little boy. And then mother said, it's high time you slept with your brother and then of course they moved him out
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Which room did you have this bath in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 in}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 the kitchen. Yes, we got one down - a long one.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How often did you bath?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh - once a week. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Which was your night?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Some - she varied it, it depended how she was for her work an
d she said - you - you two had better be in the bath tonight, or - you two you see. She sort of - to save the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 water}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 it was a big heavy thing to drag and empty you see. And it'd all got to be carried out into the yard, we had no tap in the house. There was 
a tap in the middle of the yard. And you see you'd got to empty it down a big drain there. Dad did do that. He would - do that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When did you put clean clothes on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh always Sunday night. Yes. She tried to fit -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Not Sunday morning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No,
 Sunday night. She didn't have time Sunday morning when she was preparing the dinner, you see. And - she was a beautiful washer. I'm ashamed to say I'm nothing like washing. Did everything so thorough, you know. And she taught - when I first got married s
he said, and I'll teach you to wash properly my girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Where did the family have their meals?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 In the living room. Well we'd only the room. And we had everything in there you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were there any occasions when you ate in another room?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - you see we never had any furniture in that front room.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Where did your mother cook?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
In the kitchen. Oh no, in - this was in the basement, the cellar kitchen, there was assort of place off there, one half was where the coal was stored and the half - the other half was stone slabs along and the gas stove, so she did her cooking -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She cooked by gas did she?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, we'd got gas, yes. Some people had them in the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 scullery}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  but they were so tiny - if - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 every time}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 you opened the door the gas blew out or something like - mother said, I like mine in there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When was breakfast eaten?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well - when the - the older ones were going to work, they had to be there - usually about eight in the morning or half past. And - they'd be out by - b
efore eight. And dad used to generally - there'd be some - make some tea and we'd have bread and butter, we never had anything else. And it - if we were a bit lagging, if we were going to school, come on you lot, you'll be late for school. So it wouldn't 
be much after eight. Before we'd time to get us up to wash and then have a cup of tea and bread and butter.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were you always having breakfast at eight?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well it was relays you see, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 according}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  to the time you had to be at school and at work.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have anything different on certain days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Always - always Sunday, mother always bought the very best }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 Hartley
\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 Blackcurrant}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 jam, we thought it was wonderful. And a very - oh it would be a party for ever we had a tin of salmon. But it was mostly this blackcurrant jam and she would insist that - she wouldn't buy margarine. We'll have a little less and we'll have - best butter.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Every day of the week?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, we always had - always best butter.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What did you usually have for a midday meal?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well - she did cook lovely midday - we'd have broth, you know - root vegetables and perhaps a bit of breast of mutton, made a good one. Then she'd make us meat and potato pie, we loved those. And - a rice pudding was delicious, she would make 
a lovely rice pudding or a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 Yorkshire}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  pudding. But }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 Yorkshire}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 puddings were saved for Sunday. They were a treat you see. And - think what else - sometimes she'd make us a steamed pudding and - with currants in you know or jam on, and we all loved the treacle
 ones but she said it was too messy some days and - and she wouldn't do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What about after school, what sort of meal did you have then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh just bread and butter - for tea. And - sometime you'd - you'd bet a bit of jam, but not the best jam. Sh
e'd have some other sort for you, for in the week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Blackcurrant jam on Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only on Sundays, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have anything else }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 before}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  you went to bed?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Just a drink. She'd give us a - a drink of cocoa. It was very fashionable in thos
e days. Just some small cups she kept and - you had that, but nothing else.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your mother or father bake bread?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Mother baked. But not always. It depended of course if she'd got a lot of chebonning she hadn't time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did she make jam?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Never.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Bottle fruit or vegetables?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, nothing like that. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did she make }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999 pickles?}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Or wines?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did she have any homemade medicines?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, she'd got - oh she'd some wonderful recipes for - little accidents 
in the home. And I - me sister once - she was chopping some coal and she chopped her finger and I thought it was hanging off. She said, hold on to that and found - me brother found her a - a clean cobweb, I'd never heard of such a thing before, but there 
was no dust on it, she - clean cobwebs, and she laid it in the cut, then put it down and bound it up and my sister hadn't a scar of any description.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did she often use this cobweb?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, it was the regular thing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 And - for a burn or a scald you kno
w we had pipe clay hearths, stone hearths and there was white pipeclay on them and - mum had accidentally run into me brother with a ladle full of hot water out of this little side boiler and I got it all down me back, I was only very little, and of cours
e it blistered up and that and I - I was in a great deal of pain and she said - put a clean tea cloth round me, she says, you just stay there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
And I - I remember her saying to herself as if she was reminding herself, pure home rendered lard, mixed with this
 pipeclay, and she made it into a sort of - emulsion. And she spread it on some plain linen and then got it from the back of my neck to my waist. And she kept changing it and I had to lay on me tummy. All the time. But - I haven't a scar. It healed up lov
e
ly. That was another one. Yes. Oh that was - she'd got some wonderful ideas. And if ever we got - she thought you'd got a cold coming on - when you started sniffing, we don't want the whole house on - she'd say, just go to - I think it was Riley's the che
m
ist - twopennyworth of antimanial wine and twopennyworth of sweet nitre. And there'd only be a tiny crop in the bottle of - medicine bottle. You filled it up with water, and she gave you a teaspoonful each. Antimanial wine. I never - I don't know what it 
-
 that's a new one on me but I can remember it, I fetched it so often and sweet nitre. But it was - such a - tiny drop. And for your cough she always had the fourha'porths as she called them. I can't remember it properly. Oil of - not oil of cloves - that 
was for something - that was when you had the toothache. Can't - \{ILLEGIBLE\} wine and something else. Was four things. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 And you could get twopenn'orth - four hap'orths she called it. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And it - that - you had to fill that up with water. But my word, it did it - yes.
