\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 From quite young?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh yes. Always. As soon as ever I could run about the street I had to shop. In - before we went to school in the morning we'd got to go and get the vegetables or the bread or the meat or whatever it was. And then you've got to go t
o take mother's work back or fetch her some. You seemed as if you - your time was always spoken for. You didn't get very little time to yourself you see. And I resented it. Well we all did. But it wasn't their fault. It was the - circumstances. In fact I 
t
hink they did wonders to see, now that I can look back at it with an adult mind. I couldn't then. And - and they - what really threw the spanner in the works and made me decide was going to leave home was that - when I went to this place at Redgate and I 
was an ordering clerk there and the boss said to me, you know, you could improve yourself Anne, he said, why don't you go to night school? I said, I would love to.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You were fifteen then were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Just turned. Between fifteen - fifteen and sixteen
. And so I went to Huntingdon Street night school, I looked in the paper and it - when it said there was the - you'd to go and, you know, sort of register. And they said the fee would be half a crown. 'Cos Huntingdon Street was quite near we lived - where
 
we lived. Well I never dream it was going to cost any money because I'd never paid money to go to the other school. But I thought, well - I can do chebonning for that half crown. And I had got some money, so I gave it to - I paid it and of course gave me 
this receipt. I never even thought - I was so pleased to tell them, I thought they'd be pleased. And I said, look mum, I'm going to go two nights a week to Huntingdon }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 Street}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  night school. I'm going to take English and shorthand and typing. So - I saw father looking }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 thunderclouds}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 at me, so I said, what's the matter with that? He said, and what did that cost you? Oh, I said, we had to pay half a crown entrance fee. He said, yes, and your mother could well have done with that for some dinner. Oh I never felt so
 guilty in my life. I ought to have given it to her, he said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 The best half crown you ever spent?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes, I suppose so really. And of course I was very incensed. I said, well I do try to - I want to do something better in the world, dad, I want to 
get a good job with some money attached to it. He said, you always did. He said, you're all right as you are, you're getting a good money now and you've got a good boss. I said, yes I know I have, but - I said - I want to get on. He said, you stop where y
ou are my girl, you're better there. Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What job were you actually doing then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I was order room clerk. In a lace warehouse.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And that was your second job was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 That was me second job. Went from errand girl - to this job. Yes. And I loved it but -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How long were you an order room clerk for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Seven years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So how old would you have been then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I got married from - Redgates, I got married when I was nineteen. So I was there quite a long while. Four years or five years
 perhaps. I forget exactly. But I still went to work 'cos it the war was on, and I went to work - right until - about five months before Joyce was born.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What job were you actually doing in 1911?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 1911? Well war didn't break out 'til '14. I was - 
I should have still been an Redgates, 'cos I was at Redgates when the war broke out, so I'd be there. Because - I was there - well over seven years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your parents bring you up to behave towards your brothers and sisters in a certain way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
 We weren't allowed - sometimes you know you get a bit rough and start the - and they'd let it go on just for a bit - that's quite sufficient. A word from them and we just have to - stop it. And I used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 threaten}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  me brother, you wait 'til I get at you out
side, I said, I shall pinch you. Because he would make me laugh, I've got sent from the table from a meal because he's been pulling facts at me, dad couldn't see him, and I was giggling and father said - I taught you manners and if you can't keep them at 
the table you'll go. Go on, get out. And I used to have to go in the yard. Of course he had his dinner and I used to - go out there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your parents say you should hit back or not if another child hurt you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 They were very fair in our dealings as
 far as I can see, but they wouldn't encourage us to tell tales. If I go in and say somebody's hit me, well what did you do to them? That was mother's first question. I said, oh, I hit her. Oh well, if there's two of you you're equal. You see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 If the other child hit you first what would you have been advised to do?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She'd say - I'll tell his mother when I see him, or I'll tell her mother. But of course she never did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Because she didn't go out for one thing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. She went out to the toil
et and it was across the yard and if another lady was passing she'd speak to - through the entry sort of business but - she made no special effort.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What kind of people do you think your parents hoped you would grow up to be?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I don't really think
 - they never passed any opinion. Father thought all book learning was piffle. But mother seemed to - think. She said, well - they really can't learn too much. But they didn't - they didn't know that - there'd be such a - a - you know, like it is today. Y
o
u're something lacking if you haven't had some kind of training aren't you. Well that never occurred, you see. When you left school at thirteen you got any job you could get because you was going to take five shillings home and it was gold to you. But - t
h
ey wanted you to be - you always got to be clean and tidy. At night before you went to bed your shoes were - oh they were - they'd got to be cleaned ready for school in the morning. They'd got a wonderful standard, you know, from that. And - if you tore a
 
- a pinafore or anything when you'd been playing, and you tried to hide it from them, you know, sort of business, she's say, get the needle and cotton, just mend that. She would not have you - or a button off. Oh it was a crime to have a button off. But s
he wouldn't do it, she'd make you - show you how to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did the boys sew their own buttons on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no, she did the boys.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 They were treated quite differently?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Quite different, yes. My young brother were - could get away with murder I used to say.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your parents bring you up to consider certain things important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes, clean and tidy. And they couldn't a bear a lie. My father used to say, whatever you've done you speak the truth. Mother would too. And if you - when yo
u were trying to evade something and you didn't say quite what was true, mother would say, it's no good, I know you're lying to me. That'-l do. Now you - when you're prepared to tell me the truth I'll listen.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What did they think of swearing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - father did occasionally. But mother - yes, odd times she did. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 
She was very, very angry if she swore at you. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 But -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 If you did what would have happened?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh crikey. The balloon went up. No, we never did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When grown ups were talking were you allowed to join in?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Not always, it just depended - and if they were talking - when the girls grown up see, I'd got three sisters who were quite - getting on, and if they were talking mother said, little pigs has got big ears, go on, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 get}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  out to pla
y. And I always knew she didn't want me to listen to what they were saying. But I - I wasn't interested. Although I read a lot of books on the sly, I did - will tell you that. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Where did you get hold of them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Borrowed them from school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What sort of books do you mean?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh I - I remember one and I shall never forget it. The - what - what a was - it was all about a farm and this family, about how they all - I can't remember the title. And I had to hide it, because you see reading was a
 vice, you've got something better to do than put your nose in a book, that was the expression you see. But I did love it. And if me sisters - they - when they went to the musical }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 comedy}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  once at the theatre}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 ,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 they bought the pictures in a big book and this - oh I devoured them. They gave them to me. And I used to know - they'd hum the tune and I knew the words from these books. Oh I did love it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You'd have to work in the bedrooms and she used to read under the bed and every now and then she'd thump the 
brush to make it sound as if you were working?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Working. Yes. Then you see, we - we were allowed a candle, we'd no - we'd no lights upstairs and - she'd open the stair foot door periodically - that candle's been on a long while, just put it out, it's time you were asleep, sort of business.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 If you did something your parents disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - oh they'd make your life such a misery.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How would they do this?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I don't - I can't - sort of make you feel that - make 
you feel that you'd done something over so wrong, which it was only perhaps a prank. It was when - what I principally remember - this - George that I married, well he was an orphan boy, my elder brother }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 Albert}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  ran away into the Army. I knew he'd gone, he t
old me he should, he'd had just sufficient he said. He wasn't treated like a man. And he was turned eighteen. And then one day when we got home from school mother was crying, and Albert was coming home at five for his tea. I said, where's Albert, he's lat
e
? She says, he's not coming home, he's run away. Oh, I thought that was the biggest tragedy I ever met. And - it was quite a long while before we found out he'd joined the Army and he was in Ireland. And he wrote to one of me older sisters. And mother was
 furious because he wrote to - why couldn't he write to me? She couldn't have read the letter if he'd have written it to her. You see. But - it was taking mother's place. But anyway - they smoothed things over. And }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 with}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  mother. And then he asked could he br
ing this orphan boy home. They had a - a month's furlough every so often. So - one of your lot, that's all she could say, not to be - me dad says, well it - it be a pal for Albert to go out with. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 He remembered Albert was one of all those girls see, 'cos John was too tiny to count. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
And of course George came with him. He was a Londoner. I was fascinated by his London speech, we all tried to do it. Have you come all the way from London}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 , George.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  Oh he was furious. Yes. He said, I speak just as well a}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6840067\charrsid14039999 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  you. I sa
id, you don't, you can't say salt. He said, I can. Salt. I said, that's not it. Oh. And do you know, he - when my eldest daughter first went to school - in those days they'd take them at three and a half, and - when I first took her, it was a little churc
h
 school we lived nearby and she puts - I said, she can speak quite well. They said, can she speak all right? I said, yes. But she was fairly - clear speaking. I said, but - I'm afraid some of her expressions aren't very nice, she's grandad's fellow and of
 
course you can imagine all the things he'd say to her. When I went up on some occasions, she said - are you Nottingham people Mrs Williams? You sound like a Nottingham woman but that child's definitely London. I said, she can't be, she was born in Notting
ham and she's had - she's never been to London. And - several words that - and still to this day Joyce can't say them. She says them like you, salt and there's two - what was the other word? The - the expressions and the way she phrase}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  things are quite - London. Although she's never been - she'd been now to London but she hadn't - not 'til long after she left school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When did you meet your husband, do you remember the year?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Well of course he stayed in our house. For a month. And then - he di
d say once when we were all sitting talking you know, he says - I never had a letter. And we thought he was an awful - mind you he was telling us a lie, we didn't realize 'til afterwards, 'til we found out. I said, never had a letter? He said, no. Well if
 
it comes to that I don't think I have. I said, but you'll have - I'll send you one every day when you get back. 'Course we was only doing it for fun but he believed me. I said, no, not every day, George, can't have that. But I did write to him. Well of co
u
rse when the latter came home, it was delivered while I was at work, and I'd never seen has handwriting. I said, who's the letter for? Mum says, it's yours. And when I opened it, of course, I'm too impulsive, I couldn't keep it in me own mind, I said, oh 
it's from George. That's going to stop.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How old were you then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
I should only be - not much more than sixteen. And - she wrote to me brother - she got one of me sisters to write to me brother and tell him. I was only a kid and she wasn't going to have no nonsense. He wasn't to write to me again. But }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999 anyway}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 he did write to me. And he'd - I'd taken him once to a girlfriend who I worked with home and she says, I'll take your letters for you. And that was the first big thing I did wrong, you see, I - 
George used to write to this girl in - under cover for me. And that's how we kept it up, they didn't know for ages and ages, 'cos I never told them. You see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999 
But I was very, very fond of him. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I was. But after a while - I told her once, George wants to get 
engaged to me. She says, you're only a child. Oh I shouldn't be eighteen I don't think, no. So she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999 says,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 plenty of time enough. I said, no, the war on. And he was always saying he wanted a home. He'd never been in a house like ours with all our family, and he'd enjoyed}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999  it}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  I think }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999 as}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  we did have }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999 lots}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  of fun. We did. Strange as it may seem, but we did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You say he wasn't an orphan really?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. It was quite by chance that we found out. He}{\rtlch\fcs1 \ab\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \b\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 came for a few days, he asked mother, he used to be very polite
, wrote and asked mother if he may come, he got a few days leave and he came. Grandma, father's mother, she was a - a stern old lady, we was all scared of her. But she came and - says, hm, who are you me lad? You know, the sort of way they treated childre
n
. And mother went out somewhere and I - he says, I have got a mother. My father and brother and sister don't want me and I don't want them. And of course grandma crowed, she says, ha ha ha, so we found out he'd got parents but they won't have him, he's be
e
n - he's been a naughty lad and they'll not have him. You see. And I - when I asked George quietly, is that true George, have you got parents? Oh yes, he says, I run away from them a long while ago. You see. So that was - my big sin. I deceived me mother 
and father. And at the bottom she never forgave me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When you were a little girl and did naughty things how did they punish you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - the worst was a slap across your - ears, sort of side of your head oh and sent to bed. But nothing anymore. Or -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Who did this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Mother mostly. Dad very rarely touched you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How often would this happen?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh I was always in mischief, I was. But - she wasn't - I wouldn't say it was too often. The worst - when she was chebonning she always had a ste
el thimble on and if I got on her nerves to such an extent or the others, we were skylarking about and - she'd probably be counting those stitches, I wouldn't know about then but I do now, and she'd whack - oh mum, I said, that's my head. I intended it to
 hurt you, she said, now you've got to be quiet. But we weren't cruelly treated in any way.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What would have happened if you'd told a lie?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh - yes - yes, that was the worst thing of all. You'd have got a good clout. Nothing more than that. And sent to bed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 stick}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh no. She used to have a cane and the mere threat of the cane, we never - we stopped and didn't do it - she - I'll get that cane down to you, but it was only a threat, it never - never did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did the boys get the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, just the same.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 They actually got it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes, she'd give them - if John was - or - I can think most of John because he was so near my age, he was two years younger than I and Albert was almost a young man }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 before}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  I - I can remember all about him, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You say you were always in trouble, were you by far the brightest in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no, I shouldn't think so. Well I mean - I don't know. Well Grace was with me - Grace was - Grace was wonderful, the next sister. We u
sed to talk these things over together mostly and - and - you know - she felt as much about it, because we both were very sensitive, we could feel how this }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 trouble}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  was upsetting them. And when I said, well there's ten of us. And she - she - of course there is. And she said, half'll not pay him. If we - if we do, she says, he'll not get it from all of them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you remember any particular occasion when you were punished?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. I do. Oh it was funny. I believe this was before I went to work we wasn't
 at school. And - in this back kitchen where I'm speaking - where I've told you of the slabs and the stove and mother had a great big box and a great big clothes basket and when the clothes were all washed they were all folded ready to put - ready for us 
t
o iron you see. And she - she'd been to this box for something and forgotten to put the basket back and it was on the floor. It was raining. And our John said, oh I want to go out to play. I says, well we can't - look at it. He said, I've got to go out, g
o
ing to lavatory. I said, in that case then don't get your feet wet, wipe them on the mat before you come in. And of course you know what boys are. He never wiped his feet on the mat. I man, instead of walking round to where I was, walked over the tall bas
k
et - the basket of clothes were all muddy feet all wet. I said, John look. Put it at the bottom, turn it up, don't let her see it. So of course we tipped the clothes over as neatly as we could hoping she wouldn't find it, but of course she did. But she'd 
n
ever blame John, it was always me, you see, so - we thought we'd got away with it, we were sort of chuckling. We came in one day, no tea for you. I said, what? I'm hungry. Yes, she says, and it'll perhaps teach you to do right, which is right, if you're h
ungry for a bit. She wouldn't stop it altogether, she'd keep me waiting. So she said, and - and you walked over that basket of clean clothing with your dirty fee didn't you? And I was just going to say, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 no}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 , it wasn't me. And I though well, she's not going t
o catch me. I said, I - are you sure it was me? She says, I'm quite sure. Oh and she fetched me such a clout. My ear rang - for days. And then I - I was cross then. I wouldn't say it was me brother. But when I got him outside I got hold him by the neck, h
e
 was much less than I. I said, why didn't you tell mother it was you? He said, well what was the good of her hitting me as well. He says, you had it, I couldn't take it off you. And then they wouldn't speak to you except to give you orders to do this and 
do that. Oh and you felt such an outsider. That was the worst I can ever remember. Took - she took a long while forgetting - well I should have done if I'd had to wash them again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did she ever know that she punished you wrongley?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - I wouldn
't let John - he says, I'll tell her. I says, you won't. I said, why hit you as well as me. I said, you didn't realize what you were doing. I knew the clean was there, I could have perhaps stopped you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Would you say you received the ideas of about how you had to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 behave}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  from both your parents or did one play a more important part than the other?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh mother all the time.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When you had a birthday would it be different from any other day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Very very rarely. If it - when the girls grew up and 
were older and went to work they've had a little bit of a birthday party and perhaps bought their current friend with them. But we never had any real parties - not until we were grown up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have any little presents on your birthdays at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 New clothes or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Nothing special to eat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 There would have been so many birthdays in your family wouldn't there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well there would have been, there'd be one nearly every week.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Can you remember anything you did with your mother or father together on Christmas Day?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes, now we all loved Christmas Day. We never - we always hang our stockings up and we always have the same thing in every year, but to us thing were gold. There was always a new penn
y - and a - a orange and an apple, these were luxuries alone. And a little tin of sweets and probably a little new handkerchief. An - oh we couldn't wait to - get up in the morning to find them. And then at teatime she - I don't know what it - there was a
l
ways a - she'd make some nice cakes or something like that. We always had a bit of a party at tea - and the married sisters, when me sisters were married and that when they were - got homes of their own - they'd usually come down and of course - we did se
em to have a bit of a party - nothing extravagant at all but just a party. All together.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have any musical instruments in the home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, John blew a mouth organ. Poor kid. I've seen him blue with cold when she sent him up in the attic, she
 couldn't stand it any longer.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was there anyone in the family who sang?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh yes, Julia. Yes, she used to sing in the choir at the chapel where they attended I've been - I've been and heard her, she had a lovely voice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you ever sing together as a family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh yes. If ever - you know, if we could get - most of the girls. One of them especially is music - musical comedies. We used to know nearly all those songs and one would start up and - then presently we'd join in. We loved singing, all of us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your parents play any games with you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were there any books in the house?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only - only that we'd got in - there - there was the Bible. Mother and dad's bible that I told you about. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 They}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  were on the sideboard. And - sh
e paid for one paper-Home Companion or something or Sunday Circle, I forget exactly. But - and they had the Evening Post, but there was no proper - reading. Unless -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 They had the Evening Post regularly did they?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Not always regularly. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you remember your mother or father reading?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. You see, at first they could not read. Grace and "between us - we taught them both -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You taught them both?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, 'cos mother couldn't even sign her a name when they did get a ten shilling 
pension from the state, mother couldn't sign the name Elizabeth Parker. She - I said, well you can put a cross}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 .}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 mum. But that didn't - that wasn't right to her. I guided her hand for a long while, showing her how.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you manage to teach her to read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes. But she want - she wanted to read - there was a story in this book - Sunday - you know, the - Sunday Companion or something like that - and she said to me one day, I should love to read it. So I said, well you can soon read it if you try hard. O
ur Grace said, I'll help you. Where I - I'd perhaps start it off and Grace would take - take it over when she came in and by the end they could both read the bits in - the big headlines in the Post. And they could read this story. And she lived for the da
y
 when that book come, I believe it was the highlight of her life. Yes. And she could sign her name. I taught her how to put Elizabeth Parker. I wish - I - I did ask Joyce when she was here last week. I said - she took the Bible because somebody at - Boots
 was going to - it's lovely calf, l}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
ather bound and clipped, inlaid leather, I says, try and bring grandad's Bible book will you, I'd like to show it to a friend of mine. So she - I says, did you get it bac}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 k}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  from - some friend of Boots}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999  who}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  was going to take
 it in and do it, but they left and of course }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 it\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 still not - well bring me that Bible. Well I thought she'd have been in Friday but she did - told me that she couldn't come 'til Tuesday. I should have loved to have shown it you. Because it says on it from the Ragged School.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did they ever read aloud when they'd learnt how to read?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I don't - I read to mother. Oh yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did they read aloud?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Just when they were learning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you remember a funeral in the family?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. I remember the last two babies. The funeral.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was it a sort of real funeral?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well it was very - no. One was eighteen months, that was Ruth, she was next to John. And the other little one died at about - he wasn't over - very small. But I
 was pleased about it because the lady - next door gave me a piece of cake. I said, to mother once, I was only very young myself, I said, do you think we could have another funeral and the lady would give me some cake? She was furious.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Who attended these funerals?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only just the family. And the - the sisters - those that were married and away, some of those didn't come.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you wear mourning clothes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no. Well mother had a black dress, she never had anything else but - either a black 
shawl or a black coat, they all wore black didn't they in those days. But there was no money for mourning or anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did she have a coat as she hardly ever went out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She - always the shawl. Big - big black shawl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 A crocheted one was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No, it was - no it was a - not material, it was wool. With a fringe on. But - I never saw in a coat for - oh I couldn't remember how long.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were you taken out visiting neighbours, friends or relations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Just to that aunt. I went there. I thin
k it was mother's brother, that lived in Carrington in a little cottage in Jenner Street and once mother said to Harriet, the next but one to me, take them for a walk this morning - this Sunday morning. Take them up to see - uncle Sam and want somebody, I
've forgotten the names now. And they lived in this little cottage in Jenner Street. And I - that was mother's brother. And then I went to see this other aunt who lived near us. Yes.
