\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your father ever take you visiting?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. I went to see father's brother. Uncle }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 Herbert}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 , dad's brother, used to }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 come}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 sometime, and he was - I liked him, he - he was a man who talked to children and I used to tell me dad I liked it - and me dad didn't like it. And then one of his daughters came one day and said that
 her - her dad was very poorly and he'd like to see dad. So - he looked round at mother, he says, I'd better take her with me hadn't I. And I was thrilled because he took me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Who taught you about the shopping?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So she did take you when you were little and then you took over?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No, she - there was a little shop on the corner, every - nobody went in town shopping in those days you know - on the corner of our terrace was - was this kind of fish shop and as she wanted anything - you g
o to so and so and just fetch me this. And then at the weekend she told me to write down - or Grace - whichever of us were sitting - we were the last two at school to do anything like that. And she'd tell us what how wanted and we'd write it down in a lis
t
 and she'd give us the money and we had to go there. And when we came home from work, out the lace market, she liked Maypole and butter and Chinaman tea, there was a place on Hockley that used to sell this Chinaman tea she called it, something like - and 
be sure and ask him for a bit of caper, I don't know what that was. Still don't know. And we had to call on at - we came that way home and we called and brought the tea. And we went in the Maypole and got the butter. She - because she liked it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She knew about this from previous years back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh she must have done. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Your father took you to Goose Fair didn't he?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Always to Goose Fair. Just on Saturday afternoon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you remember any other outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, he took
 us to - there was a King - I - I was in the infants school when - King Edward came to the throne, I was in four reigns - and - and - I think it was King George the VI, we were at school and there was going to be a big celebration on the Forest and - I sa
id, wouldn't like to come dad, take us? I don't want to go, he said. Come on. And Grace and John and Dad, mother wouldn't come. But he took us on to the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 Forest}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  and we heard the bands playing and - we were quite thrilled with it. We'd been from the school but that wasn't quite like going with - your own people.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You told me about going to Wilford with your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh lovely. Wilford Round House. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you remember any other outings with your parents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Our usual walk was up Clifton Grove on a Sunday night, we walked all that when we were growing up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 But your mother didn't go I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, not mother, no, she didn't. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you ever go away for a holiday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Not while we were little, they'd never had any money but - wh
en my - sister Harriet, she would be about - four or five, perhaps six years older than I, she started courting the boy next door, the policeman's son, and he - he used to ask me to go errands for him, he said, go and - I think it was threepence he used t
o
 send to the Post Office savings bank, go and take me this threepence up - up to the bank. Right Off then I'd go. I treated him like a brother because he lived next door to us. And then - he was talking to me when I got back and gave him his book and that
 and he says, I'm going to the seaside. I said, are you? Yes. He said, aren't you allowed to come. Oh no, I said, I - I can't come. Why not? Well I says, me mum and dad couldn't afford it }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 
luv}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 . So he says, oh - well, he says, we're only going to Skegness, it was half crown trip in the evening. Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 That was your only holiday was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 The - the only time I'd seen the sea. And the only holiday - you know, like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How old would you have been then roughly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 We
ll I was at school. Yes. I couldn't just tell you exactly. But mind you I used to take him his - this boy's - he used to save threepence a week in the Post Office and he used to always say to me, you'll go for me won't you? And I love it. I loved running 
a
bout. And of course - he came - he would - came and asked mother - they only lived next door - and she was always very careful. She said, you'll take care of her won't you? And he said - he said, yes, of course mother I will. And you know - have you been 
t
o Skegness recently? Have you see it at all? Oh. Well this - well I wouldn't - I might have been twelve or something like that, but the clock tower is the key point and he sat me with my back up against this clock tower - and the water - the sea - dabbled
 
at my feet and I was terrified of it. I said, oh look at it Arthur. It doesn't stop. I couldn't imagine where this water all went. Well he says, I bring you all this way to see the sea and you're frightened of it. He - he tried to ask me - he said, come o
n
, paddle. Oh no. I'll stop here. And - in those years - the last time I went, be about four or five years ago, it's about two miles, it's receded two miles nearly the sea. Yes. There's shops and - everything right down there and I - I wonder how - well I 
t
hought the sea was up against the sea tower. It was when I - yes. Washed right up at the bottom. It's a - lovely place really but of course it's Nottingham by the sea so - if you are - yes. Yes, but Mablethorpe was my favourite. Such glorious sands for th
e children.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Can you tell me how you spent Saturdays when you were a schoolgirl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes. If there was any extra shopping to be done - on we all had our weekend little chores to do. Nothing very much you know, 'cos many of - many hands get rid of it 
quickly. And - if there - often at school they ask us to take boxes for the Life Boatmen and - and - Dr }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14505167\charrsid14039999 Barnado's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 and all those kind of things and we were asked to go for so many hours, if mother could spare us, and she usually did, and we loved doing that
. And - we play about the streets and that. 'Cos there were - there was no pictures until a long time - after. The first pictures that I - ever saw were - it was - where is the - Scala now. In - it was a big - on Market Street, it was at the top there, an
d they used to - tuppence for children on a Saturday afternoon for a couple of hours.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When did that start?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
This - oh - I hadn't left school. And - if I'd perhaps run an errand for some other old lady up these streets and then I got tuppence and m
y other - the other girl that I used to run about with a lot, she'd got - plenty of pocket money, she said, come along, I'll take us - no, but I must pay my ticket, you see, and mother says, it's disgraceful. What do you want to go to pictures for? I said
, well I would like to see what they look like mum. They weren't talkies of course, they were silent.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did they have a piano?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. And this girl took me. And I never forgot it. But never went again thought. Until they opened a place on - on - what
 was that street where the fire station is - you'd think I'd remember that. Yes. We called - everybody called it Hibbits, why it was Hibbits I don't know. And as we were coming out the lace market, this was after I'd - when we were working - a man used to
 
stand with a lot of - looked like raffle tickets. Give me a penny for the ticket and you can go to the pictures tonight. But these weren't talkies. These were silent. And we - oh - we all used to crowd round and the poor man never had enough. But I've bee
n there, and I did enjoy it very much.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you spend Sunday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well we always had - we had to go to Sunday school. She - sometimes she made us go to church Sunday morning if we'd been a bit unruly. And she wanted us from under her feet. But we always had to go to Sunday school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 In the afternoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes. And then in the evening, while we lived town there, and - on Neatherley Street, there was a church mission and we were all very fond of it. The Captain - when they used to have a church 
hall, the Captain and his lady and he made the services so that we enjoyed them. We had a flower service, and we used to go and sing to - there was a very poor part, they called it the - the Marsh and - we'd go and recite to them or sing to them - they tr
ained us up to do this kind of thing. And we did love that. But we had to go. It was a - you couldn't get a - you could they only way you got out of it - you'd got to be ill and she new whether you were shamming or not. You couldn't get away with it.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have different clothes?
