\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 The bury was the burial yard?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Burial - yes. But it was open and everybody went through it you see and we never touched the graves or anything but we played on
 - on the grass. And this tin would be set up and we all gathered round it and one was on. Now, you - he'd got to kick the tin as far as he could kick it and - with his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 e}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 yes shut, and say one, two, three, scatter. And then we'd all got to hide. And bring t
he tin back you see. And - if the one who was left with the tin he was on as you might say, he got the privilege of - of kicking the tin. We loved that. Don't know what else we played.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you ever have hoops?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only the - they did, but it was ju
st people who'd got the money to buy them, we never had them. Unless somebody gave us an old one and we used to have huge fun with it, and that. And - running games and tick and all that kind of thing as we used to call it, you had to run like mad and tic
k your neighbour. Tick. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What would happened if you got dirty when you played?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well we - you'd have to watch yourself, see where you sat. Careful, she - Grace would always be looking after me in her little way. She'd say, you've dirtied that 
frock again, she'll be mad with you. But we - she was cross with us - but - she didn't sort of - very harsh. I believe at the bottom she really did.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were you free to play with anyone you pleased?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, mostly. If - if there was any child that she disliked - I don't like you playing with those }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 boys}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  from down so and so she'd say. And we just didn't have to do it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What was wrong with these?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 We never knew, she - one - she told me one - this one boy - she caught him pulling my arm for someth
ing, well children do as their a but rough - and she said, don't you do that. And this boy laughed at her. And that was the greatest insult. So when we got indoors again she said, you'll never play with that boy again. He's a most rude boy. And - I couldn
't see because I'd pulled his arm first you see, and of course she hadn't seen that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you belong to any youth organisations?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Used to go to Band of Hope, that was one night a week. And if there was - when we was in the choir in the mission - an
d we used to go one night a week sometime if we'd got some special hymns to rehearse for Sunday. Specially for the flower service and that kind of thing, we used to have special hymns and songs and some of them with good voices, they used to give a solo, 
you see, and it was - about twice a week that we went. And of course when I was older I went to night school twice a week, I liked that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When you were a schoolgirl did you have anything you might call a hobby? You crocheted did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh I was alw
ays watching - all me older sisters crocheted and with mother always being chebonning I begged her to teach me, I was dying to try it, and of course she said, a child like you doesn't want to. And then - Alice was doing some crocheting for someone and I s
a
id to her, you show me how to do it Alice. She says, well I haven't got any wool to spare. So mother used to - listen a lot you know, she said, I've got a bag with some bits of wool in. But - I haven't used them for anything as yet. So she give me one or 
two bits and Alice found me a crochet hook and from one thing it led to the other 'til -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you keep any pets?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 We used to have an old cat and he died and then - oh for many years we didn't have anything. But during - when we were in holidays fro
m school I was very fond of pets and I always was on at mum and dad to let me have one but - they sort of said no but - during this particular years holiday somebody that Grace knew who she used to work with had had a baby and I was just baby daft. And wh
en I'd done me errands for mother I said, do you think I might go and take Mrs Whatsname's baby out? Oh you and these babies, she said. Well I - I would love to. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 
Well, he says, you must ask her and be very, very careful won't you. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She says, you won't tip it
 out. Oh, I said, no mum, I'm careful. Well I took this lady's baby out - not every day, when mother could spare me. During me month off school. And she'd got a little Yorkshire Terrier dog and it had just had puppies. Well I was fascinated, I'd never see
n anything so tiny, lovely little puppies. And - she - me - she offered me money but mother always trained us we weren't to take money. I'd offered to do it and I did it because I loved it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you get this little Yorkshire Terrier puppy?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
 So when - when the - the - I was going to school on the following Monday, at the weekend I took the baby home and Topsy the little doggy was playing with all the puppies and I said, aren't they lovely. She said, do you like doggies? Oh - I said, yes. So 
s
he said, I bet your mother wouldn't let you have one. So I said well I could ask. Are they a lot of money? 'Cos first thing in your mind when you're like that, is it a lot of money and then it was put out of your mind completely if you think it is. She sa
y
s, no, but I was going to give you one because you've been such a good girl and helped me with baby. You've taken them out while I've got on with me work. Well I - oh so full of joy, I - I run every bit of the way home, it wasn't far and - dad was up in t
h
e - in the front room and there was only mum in. I stood there and she says, what are you standing there for? I says, mother - you know the lady I take the baby for. She's got a - I've told you about the puppies haven't I? So she says, yes you have. I say
s
, she's given me one, do say I can have it. I've got enough to do with you lot. Straight away. And as we're saying this father's coming down the stairs. And that - silly thing me started to cry. He said, what are you shouting at her now for? Because mum -
 
just start raising her voice then. So - I says, I can have a little puppy as a present to me but mum says no. And she says, is it only a little one? I said, oh - I says - his mother's only like that. And it was a thoroughbred. So he looked at mother, he l
o
oked at me, go on Liz, he says, let her have it. She's been a good girl, she's not played much this holiday, she's had that baby out every day. So dad, says, what does she want you to pay for it? I said, no, she's giving me it as a present. Oh dear, me fe
et never touched the ground Mother found an old piece of shawl, wrap it up carefully it's only a baby. I said, was it old enough to be taken from it's mother. But they knew it was. And we had him years. Yes. And do you know mother and dad loved that dog.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What did you call him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Mick. He was just - he was no bigger than that, you know that shaggy - they brushed him religiously, he never went on the streets, we got a yard, there was one gate for two houses and we used to yell at the people next door
 if - don't leave that gate open. You see. And he knew every word that was said - he had his own special little bit of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 an}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 old cushion and f you went in with sweets in your pocket and you rustled the paper he never left you. And I believe my father loved hi
m as much - more than anybody. He'd go - when dad sat down on the sofa he'd push his mat just to the side of him and presently }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 Mick'd}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  have his nose across dad's knee. Yes, that was one of the joys of my childhood.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How old were you when you got him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I was still at school you see, so I couldn't have been - might have been eleven or twelve, thereabouts. I loved him.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you collect anything as a schoolgirl?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you go fishing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Walks?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
 Me big brother - Albert - he used to take us sometimes - on a Sunday after we'd been to Sunday school on a Sunday morning, he would take us down Tramp Bridge, we walked all the way 'cos it was trams. And - we would stand and throw stones in and that kind
 of thing or sit on the bank and talk. And we all loved Trentbridge or he'd take us to see Arbreton occasionally. But we didn't - 'cos you see there was any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 appliances}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  to buy we knew we couldn't. Dad once chucked us a rough piece of wood out to - I said, th
ey're all laying cricket at our school. And I said, but I haven't got a bat. He chucked me this rough piece of wood and made a bit of a handle and I - of - course I had to stop, I broke a window.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have balls, could you afford a ball?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes
. Well sometimes one of the elder ones would buy us one you see, or if we went on a holiday they always brought you a little present and - say what would you like Annie? Just a little ball.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did this cricket turn into fairly serious cricket?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, I broke somebody's window - it was only a scullery window thank God.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you play any other sports?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
We played - jumping over the rope, I don't whether you ever played that did you where they highered it each time. Oh yes. and skipping of course. We were all }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 mad}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  on skipping.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you go to any theatres, how old were you when you started going to the Hippodrome and things like that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh - that was after I'd }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 left}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  school. I should be - between fifteen and sixteen.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you go to concerts or did you just give them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, we weren't very keen on concerts.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Music halls would be the Hippodrome wouldn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 The Hippodrome or the Empire. And if it was somebody that had got a big name and I'd hear the other girls, the older ones, 
talking about it, oh you ought to go and see so and so, he's very good. I saw Gracie Fields the very first time she - came to - I think it was the Hippodrome or was it the Empire, in Mr Tower of London, a sort of revue. And I never forgot her lovely voice
. But I did think she was a silly girl doing all that mucking about with the song, I wanted her to sing it straight through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You went to cinemas when you were still at school didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Went to - oh yes. I was only allowed to go the once. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your parents give you any pocket money?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh yes, Saturday ha'penny from dad always. And if mother had an extra special good week at work she would give me a penny. But I used to run errands, there were quite a few old people just round about and they'd say to mother, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 could}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  your little }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 girlie}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  just go and fetch me a few potatoes? And as sure as not one of them used to always offer me bread and jam. And I did loathe it. But I didn't say anything and I - I'd got to eat it, I daren't throw it away.
 And then - somebody must have told her I didn't like bread and jam. So the next time I went I got a penny. You see. Much better from my point of view.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You kept these pennies you earned?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You didn't have to give them to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. But she said, you want to take care of that because they'll bee something you want it for particular.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What did you spend your money on?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You'll die with laughing when I tell you. Sell - with dad's }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 ha'penny}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  we were - wealthy. Farthing ev
erlasting strip, I don't know if you've ever heard of them. It was like - caramel, in a long thin strip, it wouldn't be any more - it wouldn't be an inch wide but it was so long. Oh. Yes, it lasted and lasted and lasted. That's why we bought them really. 
And - what was the other - and aniseed balls. I loved aniseed balls. I think we got about four for a farthing. So me ha'penny went a long way you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 
And we - we'd buy - very, very rare we could afford a bit of chocolate. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 But if I'd got one or two pennies perhaps I'd been saving, and I did love chocolate.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you ever buy things like hair ribbons out of these pennies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Not 'til I went - not when I was at school. But when I went to work of course I did buy all me own hair ribbons.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You and your sisters helped your mother a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 terrific}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  amount with her housework, did anyone else help her?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I don't think so.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 If she was ill or confined to bed how did she manage?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I only once in all me life known her to stay in bed. She - she used to look
 terrible sometimes but she wouldn't stay - I'm a very strong woman, I shall get over it.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What about when she had the babies?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well of course I can't remember them being born because I should only be about three when the other three came along a
nd I - but the other elder girls were telling me. They were so annoyed about it. They said, it's not right, father should have more consideration. Dragging her down like that. And they used to have to - what father didn't do those girls had to do, and go 
to work and look after the other little ones. I can quite see their point - I couldn't at first, but looking back on it I can see it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your parents have any relatives living nearby?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, they used to - one - a - a sister of dads. The - her name was Sarah Anne but it was a Nottingham way to say - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 Aunt Sran's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  coming. I never called her anything but Aunt Saran. She was older than -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You said it as one word did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Just one word. And - she came - only - I think it was New Year's Eve, to 
see her brother. That's when I found - found out about me dad's name being Enoch, with her. And she used to come with another lady and she used to say, get that jug Annie and go and fetch a pint and a half for your did and your mum. And mother liked her. 
Else as a rule she'd got her back right up against dad's people. 'Cos she thought the old lady had robbed him of his - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 livlihood}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  you see and - she never forgave, she'd got a very unforgiving spirit and - there was just Uncle Herbert, his brother who lived on St Ansell Road, }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 and they}
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  used to send me with messages to him sometimes. And I liked me Uncle Herbert very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your parents have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Not - not that you would call friends. But she was always very friendly with the neighbours. But sh
e wouldn't have had one inside like that. Don't make neighbours when I got married - bone of your life, she says, and you don't want to tell everybody your business. She was very - reserved. When I look back on - I think now, I wonder where she'd got it f
rom. I can't think.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your father have friends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only just these men he worked with, these old men. And there was just this man at the trades council, this Mr }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12987527\charrsid14039999 Thornilow}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 , he used to speak a lot about this man. And I used to think, oh dad must thi
nk a lot about him, but we never saw him. Dad used to go to this trades council periodically, I couldn't tell you how long it was in between. But he never made - any particular friends.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 these}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  work friends who came for him come into the house and chat or did they just come and collect him?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No, they - they'd come into the house for a few minutes, but they wouldn't stay. Because if there was the children a - about you know, they'd soon get fed up. But dad has told us about them and - the peculi
ar names and that kind of thing. But - we couldn't understand.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When these friends came into the home would they be offered anything to eat or drink?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Not as a rule, it was just sit and chat. Unless - the daughters when they were married with - an
d their husband - when they come - I've heard mother say, would you like a cup of tea? But they flatly refused, you see - I could tell it was - they wouldn't take it because they'd think it was - a - a - a strain on mother. You see, and she was mostly wor
king. 'Cos they didn't come down 'til the evening.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So these friends of your father's were not really your mother's friends at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh there was one old lady. What did they call - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 Mrs.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  Howson Heather we called her. Mrs Howson Heather. She was a - 
she used to wear a - oh such lovely black cape with all jet beads on it and I think she used to be an old chebonner. But I'm not quite sure about that. But occasionally she came to see mother and she sent me to the door and - she says, I'm Mrs }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 Maltby}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 , Is L
iz in? She'd call her Liz. And that would infuriate mother in any case. But when I - mother says - tell her to come in then. And she'd sit one side of the fire and she }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 smoked}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  a clay pipe the whole time she was there. And of course our - my father never smo
ked or anything like that. Well they never had the money. And - everything she started to say - well how's the nipper? And my eye caught Gracie's and it went round }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 to all}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  - and in the end we were all laughing. And I saw - oh mother was infuriated. She said
, one of these days, when she'd gone, she said, I'll give you all a thorough good hiding. Where's your manners? She may be an old lady. But - there's nothing wrong in that. She -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You never knew her real name?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 We knew it was Mrs Maltby I think it was. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999 
Because - once at the Empire a Billy Mersen I believe his name was came down and mother says, you won't probably sneer at - Mrs Howson Heather, 'cos she copied us, she - she - she said, because she - this old lady - he was on the music halls or stage
 or something and had married her daughter, this Mr - Billy Mersen, he was a big comedian. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
I've never forgotten it, 'cos I - I found a newspaper and read all about it and - she used to look after his children while his daughter - while his wife went with h
im - round the country - they were sort of on tour. He kept her like a lady and my mother said - there's never sparing anything, if she - whatever she wanted she had and she kept those children lovely. We never saw them and she never came while she was lo
oking after these children. But when they'd perhaps gone away for a holiday together, then she'd come again and see mother.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Would she just call in casually?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Just casually.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Or did she have an invitation?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no invitation, no, it was just a casual cal.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Your mother hardly ever went out you said?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Very -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your father go and visit friends or neighbours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only very rarely. I've heard him say an odd time, I'll go round to our Herbert's. But - that - nothing - you know, 
not sort of making a preparation to go out.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When your parents had these friends round the odd time what do you think they were doing, did they just chat?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Just chat.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 They didn't have games or music or anything?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh nothing like that, no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you remember seeing a policeman around where you lived as a child, I think you said there was one living next door?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. This was Harriet's husband's father. Everybody in the terrace called him Bobby Willis, because his name was Willis. A v
ery big fat man, well - nobody was afraid of him, we all loved him I think as a matter of fact.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Everybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well - if - there used to be a couple that drank heavily in one of the houses and they used to fight on a Saturday night and so on and - and I've heard someone shout over, I shall fetch Bobby Willis to you if you don't shut up.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When you were naughty did }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 your mother}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  ever say, I'll call a policeman?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. Not like that. Because we were so - I think it was - he was more like an uncle to us. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 He was very kind to children, he loved children. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
He was very kind to me. I used to run errands for him sometimes you know. And - I always remember once on a window sill in the back yard in the summer - great big meat dishes full of - I thought they l
ooked like - wizened up bone, I said, what are those Mr Willis, nosey parker again. He said, don't you know. I said, no. Well, he says, they're walnuts. I said, well what are you doing to do them? Well, he says, I'm going to pickle them. And I never - and
 I said, well why do you have to put them in the sun. Well, he said, I've got to soften those shells you see. He was explaining it - I think I drove mother made could we have some pickled walnuts.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you like pickled walnuts?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Love them. This Bobby }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 Willis's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 wife was an invalid. She had something wrong with her legs and she used to lay on this sofa in the living room all day and he - and his - he'd got great big sons, all sons, and he had two daughters but they didn't - weren't living at home, they
 were married. And they used to do the washing and the cooking. My mother used to say she never saw anything like it. Yes. And she; used to - one of the one - the elders sons was in the Grenadier Guards, oh he was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 a fine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  man. And when he came home on leave
, that' month's leave he was singing at the top of his voice in the little scullery and doing the washing and pegging it out for his dad. There was no disgrace in it. But that man did all that, and he did cook. Most marvellous joints, thick joints, we'd n
e
ver seen them. And he once said to me, will you have your tea and let me give you a bit of bread and black pudding. And I did like black pudding but I'd never - he fried in the frying pan. I've never forgotten it. I said to mother - well - why did he - it
 
was lovely mother. She says, well - she ways, well we've always eaten them cold. But it - that's the kind of man he - he was a wonderful man I thought. When you see my dad sitting there and Mr Willis scrubbing the step or anything. And that was during his
 police duties, you see, being on shift he had more opportunity.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was it very unusual that a man did this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Oh most unusual. Oh yes. He was the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 first man}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  I ever saw or heard of doing anything. They used to sit back, wait for the meals to be do
ne and then they were off out, out to the pub are - if they went to the football match and so on. But they didn't think - I don't think they were brought up to help in the house. And -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you know any other men who did, your brothers-in-law or anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes, of course. Well - wait a minute. Julies husband when he - he - he got a lot of - he got gassed during the end of the war and he was off work with his chest and he never got work again, so - of course Julie could earn enough money, she went ou
t. Well he did. You see. But I think he - he only did it because he'd got to do, he resented it very much 'cos he was always moaning about what he'd got to do. And I said to him, well if Julie's earning the money what's the odds? And he said - well, he sa
ys, I've been a sergeant in the Army and - it was so against his }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 grain}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
. But he did keep the place clean. But he wouldn't do the upstairs. And he'd cook the meals. He - I don't know whether she'd showed him or how he learnt but he did cook the meals. But he 
was the - the other husbands - Jemima's husband didn't do anything, Alice's husband didn't.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 But the policeman would hang out the washing, the lot?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, I don't think they - all these men if they - if they did anything you - you'd have to han
g them out. Yes, yes. Yes. George did for me, I had - once when I had a very bad }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 abscess}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 under me arm, I'd washed them, I could manage doing it - my arms down but I couldn't get this arm up properly. And I was going to say perhaps our Joyce'll do it. He sa
id, I'll do it. I said, oh I wouldn't - all right he says, give us the basket. And he did, but it was the only one occasion. He would help in the house though. Those that had been soldiers did. Grace's husband wasn't - he didn't want to do any cleaning bu
t he'd do you a few potatoes and he'd put a stew in or anything like that. When she's been at work. But only if you were at work. When you were at home they sat back. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You say the policeman was very kind to children, how do you think he treated other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well we never heard him say a cross - he'd shout a bit at the kids who were making a bit of a row, that'll be enough from you, and one word from him, but he didn't sound cross. My father sounded as if he were going to kill you the next min
ute. But he's - he'd got a - a sort of deep voice. And he was brought up in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 Guild}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 Hall Cottages because I don't know whether his father was a policeman but they've always been attached to it. You see. But - all the children - nobody was frightened of Bobby Willis. Because -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Nobody at all?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No. And he was such a huge man, he would have terrified some people but of course we lived next door to him and you see you saw him at home must like a housewife. It was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 familiarity}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  I think. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was your home rented?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, rented.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you see anything of the landlord?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No, just the collector, the rent collector. We no - we had - we had to got the offices if there way anything unforeseen we'd sort of got to see about, mother used to mostly go,
 it was - oh for the past - I don't know how long she was in there, about twelve years, it was Harlow and Sons on Parliament Street. But we never knew -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you know who the landlord was?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. We had no - no idea at all.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you ever think about landlords?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, it never occurred to us because there were so few houses that were either bought or - or - or - most peoples were rented - in our -

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you remember feeling that your parents had a struggle to make ends meet?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, we 
- we'd got this very deep in us. Although mother never complained. But if we went - and asked can we - if we can have so and so. And we said, we know we'll say yes before we asked, so we stopped asking. You see, when other girls and - boys were going to h
ave such and such a thing, it may be something very trivial - and I used to see it at a theatre, I said to our Grace, she was ever so upset 'cos she couldn't give us those coppers. I said, don't ask her any more.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What difference did it make to the family when your father was ill or out of work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well she had to work, she's told me she's sat up at night, all night long, doing - she never stopped working until she couldn't see. She was quite old. But - I can't - I can't remember - this was - just the
 out of work phases were when the younger family were coming along, I wasn't born then, I didn't - mother didn't like to talk about it very much, odd things she'd tell us. And he'd tell you little bits I only knew that all her life she had this resentment
 against his mother because - they took his livelihood away. That was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 the only}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you know if they ever had help from the Guardians or the Parish or any charity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I believe I can remember her once saying - she could go without food herself 
but she couldn't see the children, I can't remember it happening but it did. And she did go to the Board of Guardians and they gave her a big loaf of bread. And that's all she ever had. 'Cos as soon as she got some chebonning again she could get some food
.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You can't remember her saying how she was treated?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh no. No. Not ever. She just - she said to us, well we can't live entirely on bread. But that was all. She'd say so to dad but she wouldn't to us children perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you feel about this?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh felt was - we felt we was cheated in some way or other. Well you particularly when you got the idea other children were having this and when you played together, why don't you have one? And you see you don't let - you didn't want - we were a
ll very loyal to her, we wouldn't - we wouldn't give her away at all, but - it hurt us. And once when I said, we can't have anything, we're poor. Don't say that word here. She was - she'd got immense pride. And I don't know where she got her standard from
. Certain things were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 right}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 and certain things were wrong, there was no grey in between those I can assure those. But she was wonderful. She - how she bought that family up, I've said since - since I'm old enough to know - well I can't imagine how ever she 
did it. She told me once she had - lived on cold water of three days so that she'd have enough - just enough to keep the children going. And charity - oh - once the - at the St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 Mary\rquote s
}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  church there they had a - a food kitchen and - the Bishop told her - any
body who's father wasn't working take a basin and go down to the food kitchen and there'd be some soup for you. Oh I saw her hackles rise straight away. 'Cos Grace and I were - always to go together so as we shouldn't spill it. She was going to let - we'v
e got a dinner for today, we'll manage.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She wouldn't let you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No. She resented other people knowing. And if at any time we had been short of anything, I got smacked once for crying - we hadn't had any dinner that particular day, I think it wa
s towards the end of the week and she hadn't got her money. And she said, what are you crying for? I said, I'm ever so hungry. Could I just have a slice of bread? She said, you know there's no bread 'there 'til we can go and get some. You be patient. And 
-
 I went into another child's house to play and they were sitting down to a gorgeous dinner. And of course we'd all been told what were good manners, you come out immediately they have a meal. And I got to the door and of course, only being a kid, me feeli
n
gs - sniffing and this lady, she was a Welsh lady, she was good, she said, what's the matter Annie? I said, I'm hungry. Well come along then, she said, there's plenty here, sit down. Mother won't let me. And she went and told me mother. Oh - you won't go 
i
n there again to play. You'll play in the yard. You see, she - I don't know where she get this immense pride from. She'd got a standard and she wasn't going to let anyone know that she fell below that standard. But - it was only her own efforts, dad didn'
t care.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did she feel she'd married beneath her do you think?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh no. No, she treated him like a lord. But - you know the newspaper at night - if by any chance you picked up, put that down, you're father's not seen it. And he had all the best cuts.
 Whatever - when there was a joint to cut. Your father'll cut that. And he had the best of everything. She'd treat - oh - I couldn't have done, I've said since I've been married, I should have said no, you don't have a blinking hit, you haven't done a thi
ng towards it. But - that was her - I don't know how to describe it. She - never made him lose his manhood. She paid everything, she wouldn't be in debt. Oh - debt was abhorrent to her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She must have been a marvellous person?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 She - well I think so. I do indeed. I know - I don't know - 'cos she - we used to think she was so harsh, always see other }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16141294\charrsid14039999 children\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 mothers giving them penny, go and have a - buy some sweets from the shop and that kind of thing and we'd look but we daren't say anything, we mustn't say we never had one. Only a ha'penny from dad on Saturday. And she must have given him that. Yes.

\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Instead of giving it direct to you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Dad's Saturday ha'penny was gold to us. Until he went to work of course it - immediately he went to work that all stopped.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When there was someone in the district who people disapproved of very strongly was there any special way in which they showed it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I don't think there was outwardly. They'd say it indoors, I know there was some people t
hat drank a lot and mother was very scathing. Good heavens, she says, the money they waste on drink. That kind of - and it made us feel that to - drink was strong. But at - I have heard - there used to be rows and fights you know.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you ever remember anyone being made to leave by what some people call rough music?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, this is new to me. No, never heard of that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Have you ever heard of an effigy being made of anybody?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only - only at bonfire night they'd make one. But not in the normal way. No. I never heard of it. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were you given any lessons by your parents, I imagine it was the opposite wasn't it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Yes. She spoke - mother spoke - sort of rough English, there was some words she didn't say correctly at all and she was ve
ry cross when I once told her. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 She would say, pass me me scissors. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
I said, mother, there's not a thin scissors. She says, you're a very rude little girl. I said, but no, you can say it right. But she wouldn't alter it. And she never said yellow in her life
. It was yalla. And I said, you - did your mother say that, where did you learn these kind of - there was one or two other words that she used and she would not change it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Can you remember any dialect words she used that have completely gone out now?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You know the word mardy don't you? That's easy. Yes, that is, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What do you mean by the word chastise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh she - if you got a smacked face or a smacked b.t.m. Yes, I suppose it's different parts of the - where they've come from. Yes. Oh 
I don't think until I was getting more grown up I ever heard the word chastise. I'll knock your head off she'd say. That was another thing she'd - never do it of course, never even hit you if she could help it. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 But if she did hit you, you knew you got thimble pie on your nut and you felt it for quite a few days.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How old were you when you first went to school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Just about three. This - the - the church schools took you when - if you could speak plainly. And it didn't matter if there was other chil
dren in the house, I believe they thought it did help the mother, you see, and it was not far from where we were living at that time in Silverwood place, we'd only got to cross the bay and I was at St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 Mary\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  school. And she took - I was in - I doubt whether I was three. I loved school though.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What time of the morning did you go?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Nine o'clock.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And when did you come back?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Twelve o'clock. And then we were - must have been half past three when we came home in the afternoon. But you see the
re were other big ones who time - if - she was a bit afraid of us crossing the road there and it - it - as I - when I was little I can always remember her hurrying Grace, go on take this child across the road, see she's safe, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you go to afternoon school as well when you were three?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And it was a church school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 It was a church school - St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 Mary\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  church. Oh yes, boys and girls.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How long did it take to get to school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Not - well, I should say ten for a child '
cos our yard was a big one as we came down then we'd got to cut across Bellargate, up this flight of steps into the - the bay and they bay - the school was the top of the bay you see. It really wasn't far but it would be for little legs you see. Bellar. T
hese were some of the old English gates you know. Bellargate, Bartergate. Didn't you know them?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You came home for your midday meal didn't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What did you think of school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Loved it. I loved it from the start.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you feel about the teachers?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 Well - odd ones - that I didn't seem to get on with at all. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
We had one that was very sarcastic and I used to think - as she - when she sort of walked down the rows and looked at - and I think - I thought she was sneerin
g at me, that's the idea I got, the woman may not have been. But - I couldn't bear that one, I never did any good for her, but the others - I was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 perfectly}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  all right. But I was so dead keen to learn.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did the teachers emphasise certain things as important in life?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What did they emphasise particularly?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Good manners - were most important. And to be truthful in all things. And tidy in your person. One teacher used to examine your shoes to see if they'd been cleaned each night, you 
see, and you were tidy when you were - and not - and if ever you got a tear in your clothes she'd say, it's high time you learnt to sew, you see. They sort of installed a - a personal pride in you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did they worry about ways of speaking?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, you - you mustn't say you and you mustn't say I'm going on. That was the usual - words.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 If you did something the teachers disapproved of what would happen?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Get the cane.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Girls the same as boys?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 For what sort of offences would you have got the cane?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh she was particularly - one teacher at ours - she was there most of - for talking, I would talk. And for talking to the other girl and not paying attention to the lesson. She'd tell me once, then the next time she'd say you
'll have the cane. She didn't - she'd just say, come on and - just - not - yes, just on the hand. It wasn't hard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your parents show an interest in your schoolwork?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, mother - mother used to say I was daft.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did they ask what you did at school?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh we didn't need any asking, it was so new to us all that we wanted to tell her.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did they ever visit the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, she had to come on one occasion. I'm trying to think what - it was second - oh I know what it was now. My 
shoes had worn out and I'd got me feet wet every time and she couldn't afford to have them repaired, they were beyond repair, they were only secondhand really when I had them. And me feet were very wet - and I saw the headmistress there, she was a very ni
c
e woman, I liked her, she says, couldn't you change your shoes child? And before I could think I said, I haven't got any more. So she didn't say any more to me but when I came home - would you give this little note to your mother? I said, yes, I will. And
 
of course when I gave it to her she said, you'd better read it. You see, because she wasn't sure of herself. And - it said - was it possible to get that child another pair of shoes, she's going to get a very bad cold getting her feet wet like that. And mo
t
her started to cry and that upset me. I said, I wish she'd never looked at me feet now. I've managed before, you see. But - I don't know whether she asked one of the other girls, my elder sister was going to work, to go - there was some place - there was 
a
 sort of a market where they'd get secondhand goods. I went - next day I think they must have been and bought a pair. Wouldn't have cost very few coppers but - at least they would have - wouldn't let the feet get wet. So I - I said, can I show them to the
 headmistress, she'll be pleased I haven't got these others on again. So mother, said, well -t would be good manners to tell her that I say thank you. But that was the only time I can remember. I was so little you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your father ever go to the school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did the other children come from similar types of home to your own?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - I did hear one of them say that if you work hard we're 
going to help you but if you're not interested, waste of our time, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 And a child that did take an interest - they did help you, you know. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And they once asked us if we'd be willing to give up our playtime, we had ten minutes break you see, and someti
mes they'd let us go into the bay to play - walk or run round. And - but if it was something in particular - we used to sometimes do songs, learn songs and things and it took a long time. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 
And - she'd say - well if you're prepared to give up a bit of your p
laytime, they did help - they worked very hard with us, 'cos we got awful to do, we got Welsh people, quite a lot of Welsh people lived in our - our - Silverdale Place, yes, and - people from all over. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 There were very few real people, you know, Nottingham people. And it must have been very difficult for them.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were there any gangs or groups in this little school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were there any children who were left out of things?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 They'd have to be very naughty indeed for anything like that to happen. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Because you - we were all - I must impress upon you that we were all terrified of teachers you know. You wait 'til you get to school, the teacher'll soon straighten you out, if you'd been naughty at home you see, and you got - went with the school in 
fear. But you see you were so tiny. You were sort of brought up with it and it didn't impress you as it would have been later on.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When did you change schools? Or did you just change departments?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, I - I had to leave St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 Mary\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  because we moved house. Went from Silverwood Place to Gordon Road because Albert was getting a big boy and mother said, I must have at least an attic to himself you see and - John was growing up and she had to do this }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  so we went to this house on Gordon Road. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 Well it wa
s much too far for John and I to go right to St Mary's. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
But at the bottom of Gordon Road we only had to cut across the Victoria Park and was Bath Street school there and I was taken there. And I stayed until - forget how old I was. We had a to take a - an 
examination to see if we were clever enough to go to - a scholarship for Huntingdon Street school, which they had - it was a - they had to pay you see. It wasn't like the scholarships there are today. These girls and boys, well they have better class peop
le, business people mostly, and if they'd got one or two vacancies they'd let them form the board - we were called the board schools you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So you went to a church school then a board school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you remember about what age you took the scholarship?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I'm not quite sure, I think - well - I shouldn't }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 be}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  quite ten because - we moved again by the time I was ten and we was on - we went on Gordon Road a long while 'cos mother didn't like it, don't know why.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And Huntingdon Street?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 It's still there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What sort of school was it?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
It was just an - yes, just call this Huntingdon Street Council school I think, or something like that. The fees weren't heavy fees. There were one or two of the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 girls}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  used to tell me, my father pays - so much a year for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And you didn't have to pay?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
You got free you see because - you'd - you'd - you'd been top of your class, I'd been in the top class at Bath Street so long they were getting tired of me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you get to school at Huntingdon Street, did it take long to walk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No, not really. Though it was - it was coming from - from - Gordon Road first and after a while we moved to - Heatherley Street off Union Road, you see, and then it wasn't really far at all. And I stayed there until I was thirteen and could - could leave.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you feel about the teachers at that school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Only one there I couldn't get on with, the others I liked. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 
And I was very, very happy there. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did the teachers at that school emphasise certain things as important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What did they think was important?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well you see - in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 my}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  class like I can remember our - our children in our group, we were made - we had got to make a dress or whatever we got on la
st so very long, we weren't allowed to come to the table without a white pinafore on. And you had to wear one. And mother wouldn't let me to Huntingdon Street without a pinafore. And I can }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 
hear}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  the gasp when I walked in with this - it was quite a nice pina
fore, it was white. And the teacher said to me, you could have hung your pinafore up in the cloakroom. Annie. I said, but mother wouldn't let - I'd soil my dress perhaps. You see. She said, well it's the rules here we don't have you in here with - a lot o
f }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 snobbishness}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 there, that was - oh - very much so. And so of course I was made to - oh in fact I rolled it up in a bundle and put it in me - schoolbook bag when I got towards school that I shouldn't have to be immolated again. But she was very cross about 
it, I told Grace and somehow or other it - it came out, she didn't mean it to do. So she says, you'd better not take them any more, she said, if that's the regulation - she said, I wonder what the pinafore - the dresses look like. Underneath.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did Grace go to the same school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You were the only one of the family to get a scholarship were you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Grace went to Bath Street 'til she left. But she would be thirteen, just the same as me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You say there was a lot of snobbery at this school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Awful lot.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Can you talk about that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes. We all had our own pegs in the cloakroom, and - yes. And I'd - I'd hung; me - hat up on this - my own peg. And they were very long cloakrooms. And as I got to the bottom - the hat hit 
me on the back, it had been thrown at me, my hat. And I heard this girl say, I'm not going to put }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 mine}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 with the dirty Bath Street lot, that's how they termed us. There was so many of us that had gone there and we were the dirty Bath Street lot and you coul
dn't live it down. And the headmistress was a snob. I always remember her name, Mrs Thorn, and I heard her once say, some little thing we'd done and she said, what could you expect from that place?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 The headmistress was as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, I thought th
at's - they took their cue from her. But I found one teacher a friend. You see we had - there was quite a lot of - sort of lessons that we'd never taken at Bath Street, particularly in English, parsing and paraphrasing. Actually, I daren't let on, I didn'
t
 know what it meant. You see. And I sat quiet. And when the teacher was walking round - noticing all, this Miss Price said - you're not getting on very well Annie. And I said, no, I - I've never done it before. You never did it? No. Oh dear, she said, I'm
 
sorry about that. It's going to keep you backwards. So she said, will you give me up a little bit of your playtime and I'll just put you on the - start you on the bottom. Of course -n no time I caught the others up and I was all right. But - she - there w
o
uld only be one teacher in that school who would ever have done that to help me because I was a Bath Street girl. You didn't get any - any help at all if you fell - and then - when it came to - they had a - a sort of - small examination in the middle of t
h
e term and - you each had to say a piece of poetry. Well I was scared stiff of this piece of poetry, I thought - I thought, well, you used to say it in the mission. I'm not going to let them worry me. And - when it came to my turn - you had to stand up an
d
 I said this bit of poetry, it wasn't very much. And I saw her looking at me and she called me to the desk, she said, Annie, she said, that was the best piece of poetry I've heard spoken she said, I'm going to give you full marks. Oh, I said, shan't be ve
ry popular shall I? She said, you naughty girl. She says, but it was the way you said it. I said, well I'm only speaking like I'm speaking to you now. Oh no you didn't she said. But she was a lovely person.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What sort of homes did these other girls come from?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh there's quite a few of them who are fairly comfortable, had good positions and got lovely clothes and that kind of thing and - they'd sort of pull aside, they wouldn't pass you on the stairs if they could help it. And they - oh they used t
o look at us if they - as if we were tramps in the street. And of course it used to get my back up a bit and I said to one girl, I said, well I shan't contaminate you, I said, and I'm not a tramp. And she tossed her head and turned. But after a while I ju
st ignored it, I thought, well - they don't know any better perhaps.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did the teachers single out some children for different treatment from the others?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, definitely. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did this show?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well if there was - anything you were p
articularly - very good at, you'd never get a chance. Oh so and so, you - come on dear, now you say it. Or when we used to read, that's something I learned which I'd never had the chance to do before. We had - had to have a book a month. And - I didn't kn
o
w where to get them from. So one - the teacher said, go to the public library, I'll give you a card. So of course - and we had to study these books and read so much that - as to get our reading perfect and pronunciation right and that kind of thing. And I
 liked it, and if I liked a thing I could do it well and if I didn't like it I didn't try.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What didn't you try at?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 History, I couldn't bear it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How old were you when you left school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I should - I wasn't - I wasn't quite thirteen. Becau
se I should have waited 'til the March when I was thirteen but dad had to go to the education officers to say that I was thirteen - he went a few days before, he didn't mean me to miss the chance for getting a job. And he got the wrong date. And I went an
d got this job. And they made me go back to school again for two - for another week because I'd been - gone a few days before.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Would you have stayed on longer if you'd had the opportunity?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I couldn't have done you see, 'cos -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 If you had been able would you have liked to have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, I should have loved to, yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you attend any part time education afterwards?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Yes. I went to Huntingdon Street }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 night school}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  for - book keeping, English - you had to take three subjects. I forget what I - what the other one was now.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was it shorthand and typing?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Yes. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 
And my boss, Mr Egbolt, he paid for me to go to - Ball's Business College on King Street. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When the typist was off, and they'd bought me a little typewriter 
to do the tickets. He said it was quicker than handwriting and he said, if you - if you're prepared to give one night of your - of your - you know - after you've left work - to go, I'll pay for you. And it was very expensive. Yes. It was only people in bu
siness who - who could afford to send their daughters there. And I loved it. Every minute of it. And that gave me the grounding you see which has kept me going ever since.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How many years did you go to evening classes?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh it was only - they were t
hree month course, I think I went to two different ones. And Mr Headgate said he'd had a letter from the principal to say they were very satisfied with me. That I'd worked hard.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you have any regrets about your education?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, not now. Because ever since I've always - each job I've taken sort of I've improved myself a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you think you benefited from attending school?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Oh yes. I often wish I'd have had a better opportunity - more opportunity to learn, or that I'd paid more att
ention because I was very full of un you see and if I didn't like - I should have been made to do the things I didn't like. I felt that it wasn't fair - I - others I could do quite - with no strain at all and I was all right. But one of the teachers expla
i
ned to me, when we were going to give the prizes out, she said, I resent giving you this prize Annie. I said, what for? What for, that was my pet question. Oh, she said, well - most of these girls have worked hard the whole term to try to get ahead. But o
f
 course - you've got ahead of them and you've played about half the time. Oh, I said, I didn't look at that - at it like that, I'm very sorry. She says, well that - you know, if I could, I wouldn't give it you. But, she said, I'm compelled to for the work
, you see. You see and it proved to me that - I should have concentrated more on the things I didn't like. Even - oh dear, yes, wasted opportunity.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 While you were at school did you have a part time job or any means of earning a little regular money?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, not while I was at school.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you do errands for people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh yes. Running about. There were some - several old couples about. And - they asked me to go and fetch some potatoes and things like that, I didn't mind, of course the shops were all very near.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you get paid for that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh I've had many a penny, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So it was not regular but you earned yourself some pocket money?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were you allowed to keep that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Mother would never take it from us. I ne
ver had more than a penny. But you see, if I went for two or three I'd save it against I might want something.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Your first full time job now, first of all you were an errand girl weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How long was that for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I didn't s
top there so long. I can't remember just exactly. I didn't - no, not long at all, because I was not quite fifteen when I went to Redgates. And I was there for over seven years.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you get the Redgates job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 Well I wanted - I used to walk up 
Heathcote Street to go along Stoney Street to the place - to Homburger's where I was the errand girl. And - this overlooker, I think I've mentioned about, she used to make me take this cat for walks and I got - I did resent it 'cos all the lads round abou
t
 going for the errands - here's the cat girl coming you know, and I - I used to - I won't stop - I don't like it, you know, and as I passed this Redgate's it was just at the top of Heathcote Street, loading on to - is it Hockley, I thin, yes, it would be 
Hockley. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
And I saw this notice outside, it said - smart girl wanted. Able to reckon and a good writing hand. So I thought, oh the overlooker at Hamburgers likes me cards that I write out for the dinners, I don't know about the reckoning. But then I didn't g
et any mess ups with the money. I thought, perhaps I will. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 And we had to be at - didn't have to be at Hamburger\rquote 
s 'til nearly nine o'clock because - the errand girls couldn't go before the - main staff were in and if they were on short time we were on shor
t time, so I called at the Redgate and I saw the manager came to me and I told him, I said, I've come in answer to your - advert for a girl. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
He looked at me. I was very small. So he says - what can you do? What have you been doing? I said, an errand girl. 
He said, hm, that won't make me think any the better of you. Anyway, he says, he bought a piece of paper, write your name and address on here. He says, can you add up? I said, oh, I think I can. And he made a little addition sum at the side. He says, do t
h
at. And I'll pass this in to Mr Headgate when he comes, he was the boss. He said, and - what wages are you getting? I said, well you know where - what errand girls get, five shillings. Oh well, he says, that won't do for a clerk, we shall have to have you
 
as a clerk I think. I were - oh I couldn't believe this was true. And - he said, call in gain - I don't think I went the next day, I think it was the day after. Can you come at the same time? And I'll have a talk with Mr Redgate about you and we'll see if
 he thinks you'll do. 'Course when I went and they took me into Mr }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 Redgate's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 private office then. He says, you look a bright girl. I said, I try to be sir. So he said, very well then, he said, how would you like to be an order room clerk? I said - no errands? He said, no. Never even said - would be a waste of time }{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
doing errands. And I loved it from the beginning. And you see the war - all he men, the managers, the chief clerk, they were all called up, all the men were.
\par Mr Redgate called us - five of us w
ho did different jobs, there was Lois the typist, I was a clerk and - one or two more packers, light packers as we called it, he called us into his office, said, well - he says - I want to know if you 'lo help me. He said, the boys have all got to go, he 
said, and we can't keep the place going and the jobs open unless we all pull together. He said, and I'm going to allocate you all a job to do in addition to your own, but, he said, I'm going to see that you're well paid. I shall give each one of you two }
{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 pound}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 a month over and above your wages. And he gave me double wages to start with. And I've had raises too. You see, I was to give all the work out to the outdoor hands, do all their wage books and help in any }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 other way}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 . Had to write all the tickets for the 
laces that went away and all that. And - Doris did the typing. I used to help her if I - if she was too busy and she helped me. We got through and we kept going and the first month he called us in, he said, I am proud of you girls. There's not anything be
e
n left. Oh with that - oh and that two pounds. He said, what are you going to do with it? To me. I said, well - one of my sisters, it was Alice who taught me thrift. She says, never throw your money away Annie. Says, I - I can earn good money but every we
e
k I go to Heathcote Street money society, it was underneath our building where I worked. You had a - you paid - a shilling a week for three years, just about three, and you got ten pounds at the end of it with the interest. And I'm thinking about this ten
 
pound. Well if I only put a shilling in it - I won't be spending it would I. So Mr Redgate said - and I showed him me book, I'd got it with me, I'd been that morning. He said, oh, he said, you beat everything you do. He said, haven't you been to any dance
s
? Oh yes. Been to - we used to go to the sixpenny hop as we called it. But that - that's all - and right from the start - I realized that don't throw away if you did get anything. And of course - I was married when I was there, he gave me a lovely silver 
t
eapot when I got married. I let my daughter have it. And it was hard to part with it but I thought well - better let her have it and - I went - I - I left when I had Joyce and then - I went back to him again. He wrote me, he said, can you put a few days i
n Annie, if it's only to do some marking for us. Marking the tickets for the lace. That's why I'm able to mark the decimals because - used to have to put twelve yard eleven meters and so }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 
on and}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  work it out because - the meters were always so much short - shorter than the yards and that kind of thing. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So you left to have Joyce?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, and then I went back again.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What would you have called yourself when you went back again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Just Mrs Williams, they called me -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I wondered if you got a work title?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well I did just the same work. Order room clerk. In a lace warehouse. You see. They said it was very essential to put that because there was order room clerks in all sorts of trades. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How long did you stay the next time?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Quite a long while. 'Cos Joyce was running about. And we were - George was - thought he was going to get his discharge because he'd signed on for twelve years in the Army. But instead of that they - they demobbed him - three months before. You see, if h
e'd have - they'd have let him - serve that full twelve years he'd - they would have been compelled to give him a pension for service, time they called it. But you see he'd lost his eye in the beginning of the war and he'd got a - they gave him a - disabi
l
ity pension for that but they got rid of him before they had to add it to - the other one you see. And then, when I knew he was coming home, well I didn't know, I'd still got these two rooms at mother's you see and I didn't know - I hoped he'd get a job. 
So of course I stopped at home at did - what I could. But of course he never did get a job for four years. Four solid years he never earned a penny. But any -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And you were still at }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 Redgate's}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 ?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, I couldn't go because he'd altered the staff round
 again and I knew very well that I couldn't have given the time, he wanted me for - if he could have taken me part time I could have done it you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you go back to chebonning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, everything at home again.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How long did you do that for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
For - quite a while. And then I went - and then Grace said to me - she was working at the embroidery place and she says, there's a - there's a machine empty next to me. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 
They wanted a ribbon ender. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I'll show you. This was at - Lenton. So I says, well, if I've got to come full time. Yes. Some dates are still in me mind, and others are not.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you get your first job, was there any difficulty in getting it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no, because - the schools didn't have everybody leaving at a certain time. Yo
u - you left when you was thirteen. You see, you didn't have to wait 'til the - no - no end of the term business, waiting so until everybody was leaving. You see. So - it wouldn't be - well, a matter of fact I - I believe we went - we went down on the Fri
day afternoon, the girl next door and I, and we both got this - these jobs before we - we was to start on the Monday.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you know the jobs were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well you - oh there was always a - label out, errand girl wanted, or something like that, or someone would tell you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So you got it yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Your parents didn't get it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What exactly did you have to do as an errand girl apart from taking the cat out?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well they - had to used a little - sort of hand thi
ng to wind cord and stuff that they put on the laces for edgings and keep all the bobbins - with the numbers, tidy in boxes so that when the machinist came out and they wanted a box - they called it pearl, it was like - the edge of the lace you see. And t
h
ey'd come and ask me for a certain number and I'd know just where to give it 'em, or I would wind them some more off card, but couldn't put the cards on the machines, had to be wound on bobbins. And I did anything they - the machinists asked me to do and 
all sorts of errands within the factory and without the factory.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What hours did you work there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well that - that depended. It was mostly from - half past eight until half past five. That's when they were working - more full time but - they had a 
lot of short time at that place and when the other - the machinists and that all went home say at four o'clock they had no more work for them, the overlooker used to say to me, you can go Annie, it's no good keeping you. You see, and I didn't work so many
 hours. That's where I used to do the chebonning you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you ever work Sundays?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no. Always Saturdays. Oh yes, there was no -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 A whole day on Saturday?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, not the whole day, always 'til twelve noon.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You weren't there very long but did anyone have holidays with pay, would you have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no, nothing like that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you remember what you were paid?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Five shillings. Normal errand girl - it was the standard rate for an errand girl.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you feel it was fair?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, we thought we were - oh we were right. Five shillings was an enormous amount of money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you give this to your mother?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 All of it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 All of it. And she always gave us threepence to start off, that was our pocket money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And it was spent on general housekeeping I suppose?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh yes. She couldn't have managed otherwise you see with all the other girls, they paid their board, that meant just for their food and that but they bought all their own clothing,
 but until I could earn enough to pay me clothing - and the others - mother had to find our clothes, but we always tipped - gave her our packet just as we got it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you get on with the other people you worked with?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Very well, there was ju
st odd ones that were a bit - erratic, one or two you know that used to - think they - well, I was a child you know and they couldn't - every little thing - blame it onto her so everything went wrong that they could get a go at me they did. But I didn't l
et them bully me because I liked the other girls and they liked me. Just an odd one or two.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh, very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you feel about him?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I liked him very much.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you feel about the work?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh - well I liked it, really, I liked the indoor part but - I loathed taking this cat out. Oh - and you see they were so huge, these long rooms, they went right across the top of the factory, it was }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 five floors}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  up, I think it's pulled down now if I remember rightly, and there was the machines all in this room and the far room the - clippers and }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 calipers}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 used to sit in little groups and work in there and there was no machinery in there so that you could shout your head off in that room and nobody would hear 
you in this room. And I had to put big sheets of brown paper down near the hoist, one of those hand hoist things that you pull up, for the cat to use as a lavatory, and I had to fill it with sawdust each - and take it up each day and carry it down these -
 all these flights of stairs, there was no lift or anything, to the dustbin so it wouldn't smell or anything. That was the part I didn't like.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did most of these places have cats to keep the mice down?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - quite a lot - we had a - there were a lot of rats and mice.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 There was a reason for this, it wasn't just somebody's pet was it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh definitely. Oh yes, it was the overlookers pet, she bought it herself as a little one but - they were very pleased she did because - you'd go some days and on the benches where - where lace had been left }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 when}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 machinist}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 got up, it's been all - dirt form them, from mice and rats too. On the lace and they had to sort of try to scrub it clean. And it smelt you - oh open the door sometimes. You could smell it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You told me how you found your - second job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, I went in answer - there was the bit of notice outside - a girl wanted, quick at figures, or something like that.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What exactly }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 you had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  to do in that job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 Well - the - this was a -
 Levers lace place and - the - it used to - they'd come in great big bundles and then these lace duchesses that we used to call them - they - well, middle women really, and they'd got huge hampers on wheels and - they'd take the - oh the - biggest - big a
s beds sometimes - hundreds and hundreds -}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And they'd give it to the outworkers?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
And they'd take it home and draw it or - scallop it, it just depended what wanted doing to it. And then it was brought into the factory and - and made up in - ever s
o fancy - little blue pieces of paper and bows on it or - my job was to ticket this all and watch - check from the books for each order that -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You had to measure it as well?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no, I never had - that was all done upstairs into the workroom. In t
he order room I had to put these gilt tickets on, the yards and the meters on each one and the number and - what order it was for. Because you see, there's perhaps be one particular number was very popular and I'd perhaps have to get five different orders
 at time, they piled them up and then we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 had}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 to make them into little parcels and - they were called - assortments. Then the boys would pack them in these huge cases and they weren't all over the world.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What hours did you work there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh I - nine 
o'clock, always an office girl then. Once I was in - I was an order - when you was clerk you weren't any more an errand girl, you came at nine o'clock. Nine 'til six. But if you had your booking at the days and you'd got all your booking to do, you see, I
 
had to book all this work out to these - outdoor hands and we'd got twenty of them and it was very complicated and I had to have a price book with all the different prices. Some were two three a dozen, some were a penny farthing a dozen and so on. I must 
be sure to get those all correct. And I'd got to put this down in my daybook. So that could go into the office to be checked when I made the - minute out for them. And so of course if they haven't finished them - the - have you done your books Annie? }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid14878678\charrsid14039999 No, I've not finished, I've had a lot today, Mr Redgate. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Very well then, finish them off, then you can go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you ever work Sundays there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, not ever. Nor Saturday. Twelve o'clock. To - I mean Saturday afternoon, I'm speaking of. Work 'til twelve.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have any holidays with pay when you were a clerk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No, I don't know. No, we just got the ordinary - annual holidays, Bank Holiday and those kind of things, but there was no regular - nobody sort of had a holiday for themselves, you see, w
e just had the - Bank Holiday, Easter and Christmas and so on, but nothing else.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What were you paid as a clerk?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well I were - I was getting the five shillings at the - as errand girl and then - and he gave me seven and six to start, that was - 
and I thought that was wonderful. And - every year I had a rise. And then when the war broke out and I got this two pound a month bonus for all the men you see I was getting quiet a good -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What would you have been getting at the beginning of the war?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Can't just remember for sure. The minimum rate - was - twelve shillings a week, that was the top wages a girl got when she was twenty-one, you see, you started at five shillings and if you were quick or good at your work you gradually rose until you 
got that twelve shillings. That was the sort of - standard rate. Yes. But I believe the clerks got more, I'm sure I got more than my sisters because they used to say, you don't - you don't do half the work I do and yet you get more money than me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 And during the war you got the extra two pounds?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 We got the extra. Yes, that's right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So it must have jumped up then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes, it did, quite a bit.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When you were getting the seven and six did you give any money of to your mother, was it the same pattern again?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
No, she made me pay my board then. When you began to get anything like an amount of money and she thought that you could clothes yourself and - like you paid - like the elder girls, you paid you board, it was called paying your 
board. And there was a standard rate. Don't know whatever she - I - I think it used to be seven and six and I'm not quite sure about this, and I know that there used to be lots of - would say haven't paid me board yet. And they would say - oh, I've got se
ven and six. Whether they'd got seven and six towards it or whether the - they'd got the whole seven and six. If they were very short of work they still had to pay that you see of course.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 When you were only earning seven and six you would still have given it to your mother
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How would you have clothed yourself then?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well she would - well - I - I'd be - you see, when we was chebonning, getting that - and we were doing chebonning you see, so I'd got the - I'd always got some money for my clothing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you get on with the people you worked with here?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Very well indeed.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did your employer treat you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Extremely well, I'd never met a man like him before, he was - I think one of the most exceptional bosses I've ev
er come across. He - had them - he thought of the workers comfort. Others you see, they sort of - you was just a - a shied for then walk by you but - a man got the toothache one day and it was warm and I'd got the window open because I liked the window op
e
n, and the boss's son - he was a very nice man, he walked by, he said, you know you'll never get that toothache better like this. We must have the window closed. And there was a sweet on the desk somebody had given him, I wouldn't have it, I put it down, 
he says, no don't eat those wretched sweets. There was all - because it pained. He was thoughtful.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you know it was a good firm when you happened to go to it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I knew nothing about it at all. I'd just seen it as I passed daily going to the other place. No, didn't know anybody there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did they pay for many people to do these evening courses?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2979937\charrsid14039999 
Only - I don't know, I think it was if they thought you'd got any promise, you see, and when he bought me this little old typewriter, because I - o
dd times I'd get a drop of ink on the lace when I was writing these tickets, some of them were very small and I had to learn to write small, and always a child writes big, but I got - I could do all right. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 But anyway - he told me what to do. If I'd got ink
 on I could take this little packet back to the workroom to the overlooker and I ask her - she'd undo it and work it in so that it didn't show on the crease. Tricks of the trade. And - you know, I didn't - I met - somebody nudged me elbow. I think one or 
two bi}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2979937\charrsid14039999 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
s of ink got on - frequently, Mr Redgate came by, he says - and he saw me do one. He says, you know Annie, we can't have that. I said, no Sir, I'm sorry. 'Cos ball point pens weren't even thought of in those days. You see. So he said, could you type 
those little tickets? I said, oh I've done quite a lot on Doris's machine, that was the typist. Well come along and show me how you do them. Of course - we used to play about, we hadn't always - we weren't - you know - sort of grinding all he time, we had
 to work 'til the work came down and then we had to work like slaves to get it all finished and I showed him, I did quite a lot - He said, it's much }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2979937\charrsid14039999 quicker}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 . I says, yes, I like - he said, do you like typing? I }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15204605\charrsid14039999 said}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
? Oh yes. So no more was said and then the
 next - it was only an old one. But I used it for all the tickets, I never wrote any more after that. And - when she was off ill - the typist was off ill for a long while and - the manager came to me, he said, I can't get my letters written now Doris is a
w
ay, wanted the letters typing. So he says, you type those tickets, could you type a letter for me? I said, I can't do shorthand, I've not shorthand. Well, he says - we'll see what we can do. And of course I did him a few letters, he dictated them to me, a
n
d he must have told Mr Redgage that I'd done these letters quite satisfactorily. And then he came to me and he said, are you willing to give up a couple of your nights off when you've done work? Of course I was thrilled to bits. And he paid those fees and
 
bought me books, and they were quite expensive in those days. And of course when it was time - she was off about six months, she'd a long illness, and I kept them all going. There was two - there was - Mr - Mr Redgate's letters, Mr Price's letters, George
's letters, and my own letters and - always the price lists, I had to type all these, and I - I liked doing it. And I suppose really it - it did for them. You see, but it was knowledge to me - I used it in many ways after you see.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What jobs did you do after this, can you tell me?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You were telling me your sister told you of a job?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes. To embroider. You see, I stayed - I went up to work 'til - end of January when Joyce was born in the June, you see, and I couldn't go any longer. An
d then I got - it was all work at home what I could get, but it was very poor paid and it was very erratic. You may have a lot of work one week, the next week you'd nothing. You see, George wasn't earning anything. So of course I had to do my work. And so
 she said, there's a - there's a machine against me, she said, happen you'll soon take to it, you're not daft. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2979937\charrsid14039999 That's how they used to express it to you, you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 So I said, oh, I said, I don't know, I said, but if it was writing his tickets out for him I c
ould do that all right. So she says, well, I'll take you down tomorrow when I go. It was right down Lenton. And I was frightened to death of the machines, strangely enough, yes, scared. They were only like little ordinary sewing machines what we had to us
e but no teeth in them, you see, and you had to used these hoops to make the pattern by movement of your hand - the same thing - like embroidery
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What was the job called?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Mending. You }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2979937\charrsid14039999 were}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  a Swiss embroidery mender
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Why would you call that mending when you're not mending?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
You are mending. Well - it was a hole in the embroidery but not in the met it was made on. You see - this - this Swiss embroidery - well it was made on nylon, it was made on fine silk and the machines were ten yards lon
g, there was two tiers, one belong and one above, made twenty yards at once. Hundreds of thousands of needles, those - little girls used to have to thread up. Well - if a bobbin of silk or cotton }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2979937\charrsid14039999 broke}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  it left a gap in the embroidery. The net wouldn't be b
roken. So they'd bring them to the menders, used to have to pull them on a counter, a specially black painted }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2979937\charrsid14039999 shiny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 counter to show it up and tie them up then take them to our little machines and you'd stitch them tight - have you got it. Fit them ever so tight into the hoops and you followed from the pattern above or below or either }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid2979937\charrsid14039999 sides}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  and you made it fit in, you couldn't tell we'd mended it.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How did you join the ends?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You just put - put your needle in and pull the thread through and then cut
 it off when you'd finished you see so - or you worked over it. But there was a lot of raised work. They had to work several times backwards and forwards, then you got to jump across it, the thick stems, you see. And flowers, we used to embroider flowers 
all over everything because you were drawing with them but with machinery and you can -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did it take a lot of learning?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Quite a long while before you could get any speed. You see, and you'd got to have a bit of a gift for it for - Grace used to li
ke it, she said, oh, she says, they've never seen mine. Of course I didn't give the - hadn't given me heart to it like I did to the clerical work and I wanted to do typing and that kind of thing at the back and I wasn't - she said, you don't give your ful
l attention to it. And then all of a sudden it sort of comes to you. And I was quite quick, I am very good 'cos it's very well paid. We were piece rates you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You were very skilled weren't you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - it was not for the skill, it was the amount you could get through.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How long did you do that for?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Roughly on and off - I - I had - the break for the war when I went in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid12987527\charrsid14039999 
