to be educated and the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 uneducated.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
 And I wished - I did so want to do - I said, if I'd have had a chance to have gone to a university I might have been able to make some - I might have made a false report, I might not even have done anything, but I felt as 
if I wanted the chance. You see, I didn't - I couldn't - I knew I couldn't possibly have it, but I just felt -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Nowadays you might have done?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes. I've taught me lots - lots of things myself since I've been - you know - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 left}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  - since I've been 
on me own. I - latter part of the time at Redgate there was this Spaniard came and brought us a lot of orders and he couldn't speak very much English and he used to ask me to type the - these prices lists out in Spanish. Oh, I couldn't possibly do that. S
o
 he said, I'll help you. And he used to sit beside the typewrite and speak every word, and before I knew it - do you know, I could do it ever so quick. And I was fascinated. I said, I would like to speak like you. I teach you, he said. You know. 'Course h
e never did 'cos never had time. But I could type those letters in Spanish and they all used to laugh and say, well what's this - and the other girls couldn't - I said, oh I'm not telling you.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you think of people in different social classes or groups in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes, very much so. You - and another thing, where you lived mattered. You say, oh those awful people who lived on the Bottoms. The same as you'll hear today, those awful people on St Ansell Road, from the slums. And at one time - I 
know some families that were - weren't - it was quiet, a nice residential road. I lived on Union Road which was a sort of carry on of it and they were nice people, really nice people. And there was the Bottoms. The Bottoms was - they run along from - the 
b
ottom of Bath Street and Beck Street and down there and all those - lot of little back to back houses and - all summer through you could see these ladies with their beautiful white aprons sitting on the doorsteps if it was warm - drawing and scalloping la
ce and they looked spotless and their little places were spotless. But they were low, they lived on the Bottoms, you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I know }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid2979937\charrsid14039999 St Ansell}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  Road very well.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you? Oh. My sister lived there forty years. She said.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You wouldn't recognize it now on on side, it's gone?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Yes, so they tell me. I've not seen it but she told me. And there was the Mile Marsh, that was the worst of all in Nottingham, because we did have a lot of drunks down there, it was the back of the Midland station. We wouldn't
 go down there by yourself. No. Even the policemen patrolled in twos.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What sort of social class would you say you belonged to yourself?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh working class.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What sort of people belonged to the same class?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Practically - Practically all t
he children was - in our status as we were - you know - and so on, we all had to go out to work for our livings and we were rather proud we were the working class. You see, but - we never aspired to be anything else because if we'd got a decent job we wer
e happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What other sort of classes were there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well there was - we used to laugh at the high school boys with those special coats on, you know, what did they used to call them - bum stars one lad used to call - little short coat. And - mostly it
 was the clothes they wore. And if we were playing about and they walked sedately by us and looked - sort of looked down on us and of course we should laugh. Most rude of course, but we did it. Said, who does they think thou are. And someone with us - oh 
look, King George coming, just look. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 
You know, it was a very, very rude but it was instilled in us, we were all - and business people, people who had got a shop or somebody, that was another thing. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
You couldn't compete with those, you was just an ordinary - working girl, you'd no opportunity - of sort of meeting on a level ground with them.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Any other groups you can think of?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well the bosses, they were in a class apart.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Can you remember being brought up to treat people of one sort differently from people of another sort?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh yes, it was terrible thing to have to live by - we had a French family come to live in - just at the back of our house and they could speak a little English - but everybody sort of laughed at them. And I used to say, i
t's awful, laughing at those people, they can't help being French. And - when we got to Huntingdon Street, see, we had never taken another language 'til we got there, we were taking French. And I used to - I got to air mine off on this - Jenny - }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 Jenny}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  Brut
er, I always remember that girl's name - she said, you're very kind. I said, well, I want to learn your French. She said, you - you teach me your English. I like it better. And we got to we could converse quite well but - they came from France and I don't
 think their parents - had - I've gone in - she went - asked me in to tea one day. Oh and it was a torture to me, I couldn't tell a word - they were going too fast for me.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were you sort of brought up to treat the bosses differently from other people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes. Oh -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 In what sort of way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well - it was a sort of grapevine, it - you'll find it in every factory - every place and wherever you go - if you're up to something that you shouldn't be there was - you know - just a - and }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 everybody\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  know, the bosses say, I'm just watching what she's doing, you know, that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were you ever told to curtsey to people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, not ever. No, that was passed. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 
But we were supposed to stand up when Mr Redgate came - he had a private office yo
u see and when he came into the order room he had to come down a little passage and then - if he looked at you, you knew he was going to - wanted you to - tell you something or to ask you to do something. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You automatically got up. From your stool. But nothing else, no. And we always called him sir. We didn't call the others. Mr Redgate was sir.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was there anyone else you came across you called sir?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh in the fire service it was all sir. And 1 anybody above you in rank.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 But pre 1918?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh I don't know about that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Anyone you had to call master or madam in those days?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Do you remember anyone showing respect to your parents in these ways?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Just in the usual way. We were - we were - we had to call mother or father - none of this business of calling them christian names.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You didn't know what your father's name was for years did you?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No I didn't.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was this usual?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes. Because we never heard it. Mother never addressed him by his Christian name, and o
nly - no, she didn't say Mr - it'd be dad. You see. And also I didn't know mother's name, I asked her particularly because he always called her mother in front of us. It just happened, yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I thought perhaps they were }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 still}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  on the Mr and Mrs?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no. No, it was just mum and dad. Or mother - she would insist we said mother and father you see.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 In the district you lived in who were considered the most important people?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well at the - this - it was a sort of terrace that we lived in and ther
e was a big house on each end that had more rooms and that and one of them was a milk man, he'd got a great big shed full of his milk churns, he was supposed to be the }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 nobles (?)}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  as they call it, that's the delivery one you know. And then at the other end 
there was two maiden ladies who let rooms to people. And they'd got a status. You had to - and if you played around about their house - get away from here, you're making }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 anoise}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 , and that kind of thing. And we sort of semi respected them. Yes, because they were old and we knew they'd got to get their living. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 
My mother once explained it, she said, you see, they can't do with a lot of kids racing round, 'cos we used to play tin- lurky and that kind of thing.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you come in contact with them otherwise?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. Oh no, they never spoke to us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What about the shopkeepers in your area, who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well they were - they were pretty friendly with everybody. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 
Who was a good customer but if ever you - there's one who didn't pay you, you got a bad name straight away.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What about the clergy, who did they associate with?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well - I never even saw them at home. 'Cos we used to go to St - first we went to St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 Anne\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  church because it was the nearest. And then when Joyce started school 
I - I got her into St Marks school which was a bit nearer, that was a church school. Of course I wanted her to go because she would keep running away. And - we used to go then - then that's when we went - went to the mission, St Marks mission and I was ma
rried from there and we all went there after that. But for a short time we }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 did}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  go to St }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 Anne\rquote s}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  because it was near for us.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Before the 1914-18 war who did teachers associate with, do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Teachers? Oh only with other teachers - oh she - the t
eacher was - you all looked up to them, in many ways. And they were sort of - in a class apart from us. You had to - please Miss, may I so and so. And stand at the desk with your hands behind you }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 if}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  you wanted to make a request.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Who did employers associate with? Do you know?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No, not ever.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 It's no good asking you about farmers is it?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What sort of people would you say went to Church?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well at one time when I was quite young everybody went - from the poorest right up
 - there was only the people who drank, we used to have quite a few who did drink, they didn't go. But for the rest - and what I noticed and thought about, even if their parents didn't go they made their children go.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 What sort of people went to chapel?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, there was quite a few chapel people. They were the same as we were, just working people.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 They weren't very different in any way?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. No.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Where you lived did all the people in the working class have the same standard of living or would you say there were different groups?

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Oh yes, there were - well - one or two always seemed as if - my mother had the expression - they've seen better days they have you know. She thought they'd come down to come to - like where we were. But we
 never knew, they sort of kept it to themselves. I played with one girl a bit when she was new and they'd had a public house. Oh and we thought that was a marvellous thing. You see, they - they'd had - come down in the world, because they'd - don't know w
hether she'd - something had happened that they'd given up the business and they were just ordinary like us then. But they never sort of - mixed - altogether. The kids played a bit together but not the other ones - there was older ones but they didn't.

\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Could you describe another family like yours?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 They were mostly like yours?
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were there any other sots of families?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Well they're pretty much the same, they all went out to work, they - they worked hard. There were q
uite a few miners. Who lived there. And there was Bobby Willis. And there was quite - four or five big families like ours. That - as sure as Alice married the sailor boy, he'd got seven sisters and three brothers. He was a big family, the same as Mr Willi
s's - oh he hadn't got so many but he'd got quite a few. That was next - either side of us. Where - there was another big family, oh - }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16337627\charrsid14039999 Roberts}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
