ou - you could see it, he wouldn't come in if he could help it. And he ran away and ran away 'til they put him in a - a school, you know, a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6301576\charrsid14039999 whatsername}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  school - oh I can't say the name. Somewhere in Kent it was. And of course, when he had - when he'd finis
hed his time in the school he said - well, they said, do you want to go home? He said, no. He wanted to go in the Army, see, he went straight to the Army, before - I think he be about fifteen. You see, and of course that's how - my brother was in the Army
,
 in the band and these band boys used to do little jobs for the men for the sake of coppers sort of business you see, and of course he told them that he'd got no - people. And my mother was so sorry for him. And Albert got all our sympathy. All the girls 
a
t home said, fancy poor lad, he don't get any letters and he's got no home to go and have his furlough, can I bring him home? So mother said, oh goodness I've got enough her now, but, she said, we'll squeeze one more in, he can squeeze out - he'll have to
 
go with Albert then, sleep in Albert's bed. And that's how it was we sort of we got to know each other and then he went - called up - he went in 1914, he was still in the Army when the war broke out and he went to France. And I think it was the - was it t
he second eight days leave he had that we got married. He so wanted a home of his own, he always talked about - you wait 'til we got married and I've got - if it's only a tiny bit of home and I knew then the longing he must have had for his home.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 He probably felt himself an orphan?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh - yes. No, he felt it. Although he knew where she was all right.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you save up before getting married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes. Yes. I worked frightfully hard, saved every penny I could.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did your parents help you in setting up home?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh no. They hadn't anything.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Were you officially engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How long were you engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 About a year. Yes.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Was there a period when you were going to get engaged?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. We talked - we talked
 about it a lot. And he said, wait - wait 'til my ship comes in, I shall buy you a ring. I said, oh I don't know as it matters because we hadn't very much money, he didn't get a lot of money in those days. But he - he backed a horse or something and son s
ome money.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Could you describe the wedding?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes, just a quiet family wedding, at home. And - my sister Grace she said, shall I be your }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6301576\charrsid14039999 bridesmaid}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 ? I said, yes. And - me brother John, you see George had no men friends, he couldn't bring them down f
rom - he was in Scotland then - not Scotland, Sunderland, stayed in Sunderland then and he couldn't bring them down, they were - you know, during the war, so John said - well, and father gave me away and there was just - Doris and Florrie and - all me sis
ters of course. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6301576\charrsid14039999 They waited at the table and made such a to do, tied them up, big bows on their hair as if they was waitresses. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 They'd got a sense of humour. Just had a quiet little time. I was married in me own church, St Marks church. And -
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you wear anything special?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. Well I - I did do because - the girl next door was a friend of mine and she was a marvellous dressmaker, used to make all our }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6301576\charrsid14039999 clothes}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  at one time, and I said I was going to have a costume. Oh, she said, don't do that, she 
said. I'd love to do you a white dress. I said, well they're dear. She said, well never mind. You see, and she did one in white taffeta wholly by hand. Not a - not a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid4399113\charrsid14039999 stitch}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  in the machine. She joined the seams together with that - faggot stitch you know. Y
es. Because - because we were friendly, we lived next doors so many years - and she - oh I couldn't let you - you know you're not going to church in a costume. You know Yes, I was very happy.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did people give you presents?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh I'd go a whole - big
 packing case up in the attic full of - because you see I was in charge of all the outdoor women, they vied with each other - four people will give presents Annie. I've begged them all. I said, join together but don't - I said - you can't afford. I heard 
o
ne or two bits what they were saying. So I said, keep out of it, you don't get married every end of the week, sort of business. I had a caseful. Even the woman at the corner shop sent me the most beautiful trinket set. I - I can't remember what - and the 
b
oss gave me the silver teapot. And then there was a case of cutlery from the men staff. Oh - and all me sisters brought me things. All me utensils, I'd - I'd practically - you know, I could have started housekeeping. I had half a tea service from mother. 
A
nd then one other the girls, they - two joined together, half a dinner service to match you see. Oh, I had some wonderful presents, I did. I had - they all gave me a blue garter. I said, whatever's that for? Oh, you must wear something blue on your weddin
g day. And I had to have a blue garter - a blue fancy garter. One of the girls gave it me.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have to wear something old?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Oh yes. Yes, something old, something new, something borrowed and something blue, and I was - I said, oh I can't borrow
 anything, I must have me own things, but a friend of Grace's who worked with us, she'd be married just not long before and when two or three days before the wedding she bought this parcel home she said, Ethel says you've got to wear her wedding veil, it'
ll be good luck for you. And - it was a beautiful thing. I hadn't anticipated doing that.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Did you have a honeymoon?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 No. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6301576\charrsid14039999 He'd only got a day's leave. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 But - we went to the theatre once. We counted up how much money we'd got and - George said, well 
I would have liked to have taken to the theatre, not at here, it was the Arcadian. He did too, very fond of music. And when we got - Doris lived out at Long Heaton, and she said, well you've got to come to me for a weekend, you can't stay - just have your
 Saturday on the - it was such a job to cram them all in you see, all of them kept - well, you'll come to us, we'll do such and such a thing. Well I couldn't be at them all.
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You lived with your parents after you were married?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. I stayed there.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 How long did you stay there?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 I was there - over four years after I married. See I was married in 1917.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 That'd he 'til 1921?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Yes. You see, couldn't get houses, it was all the soldiers - the married people who'd gone into the Army wer
e coming back and they wanted the houses.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 You said your husband was out of work for four years?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Four years. He had no trade you see. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid6301576\charrsid14039999 He\rquote d}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 
\ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  gone into the Army as a boy. And all - all he knew about was beating drums and - music and that kind of thing.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid8407077 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 Could you tell me his jobs after that?
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid15820647 AW  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999 
Well - well he - he never kept anything for very long because you see it was - so little money - he'd got to be able to do something. The first job -
