l
e. They said, yes, they can stop his and not his wife and children, by that time I'd got Grace you see, there was two of them. So of course they made an appeal for it and they gave me a little allowance. Not much it wasn't. But you see, I got this bit of 
work all the time. So we got through. And he went away somewhere, forget where it were. I know, it was through the British Legion again. One of them said, you ought to go to one of these 'ere - rehabilitation }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 
\insrsid6301576\charrsid14039999 centres,}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \insrsid16006220\charrsid14039999  George, he says, and get your self trai
ned for a job, something worthwhile. So he said, I don't want to - I don't want to learn any more at my time of life. He really thought he - he did a bit of window cleaning or anything like that, but he wouldn't do a proper job. But anyway this time they 
s
ent him to a - a - to see some people, I forget who they was now, and they sent him to - a ammunitions firm in Leicester that - that was training people like George with a handicap to do some job in it and - oh he fully learned engineer in that fortnight 
y
ou see, and he stayed at Leicester coming home occasionally for quite a long while. And then he went - where else he went - he went to work at somewhere else. Cromford - Cromford - somewhere - what was the North - and then he - he had - he - I don't know 
